# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ancient-egyptian-trade
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/4th-millennium-bce] The **4th millennium BC** spanned the years 4000 BC to 3001 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/4th-millennium-bce] Some of the major changes in human culture during this time included the beginning of the Bronze Age and the invention of writing, which played a major role in starting recorded history.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/4th-millennium-bce] The city states of Sumer and the (Predynastic) Kingdom of Egypt were established and grew to prominence.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/4th-millennium-bce] Agriculture spread widely across Eurasia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/4th-millennium-bce] World population growth relaxed after the burst that came about from the Neolithic Revolution.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/4th-millennium-bce] World population was largely stable in this time at roughly 50 million, growing at an average of 0.027% per year.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/4th-millennium-bce] Sub-Saharan Africa remains in the Paleolithic period, except for the earliest neolithization of the Sahel following the desiccation of the Sahara in c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/4th-millennium-bce] As the grasslands of the Sahara began drying after 3900 BC, herders spread into the Nile Valley and into eastern Africa (Eburan 5, Elmenteitan).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/4th-millennium-bce] The desiccation of the Sahara and the associated neolithisation of West Africa is also cited as a possible cause for the dispersal of the Niger-Congo linguistic phylum.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/4th-millennium-bce] Based on studies by glaciologist Lonnie Thompson, professor at Ohio State University and researcher with the Byrd Polar Research Center, a number of indicators shows there was a global change in climate 5,200 years ago, probably due to a drop in solar energy output.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] The **5th millennium BC** spanned the years 5000 BC to 4001 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] It is impossible to precisely date events that happened around the time of this millennium and all dates mentioned here are estimates mostly based on geological and anthropological analysis.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] The rapid world population growth of the previous millennium, caused by the Neolithic Revolution, is believed to have slowed and become fairly stable.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] It has been estimated that there were around forty million people worldwide by 5000 BC, growing to 100 million by the Middle Bronze Age c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] The Stentinello culture stretches from Sicily and Calabria to the Aeolian Islands representing cultural focus on seafaring and maritime trade at this time.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Sardinia has close trade relations with the Mediterranean Neolithic communities of southern France, the Iberian Peninsula, the Italian peninsula and Sicily and is a major participant of the silver trade.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Overall, the Ubaid period experiences sporadic but controlled growth of socially stratified settlements, with communal areas, segregation of classes per quarters and complex social stratification.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Increased conflict between democratic councils, large scale chiefdoms, royalties, polities and imperial-like aspirations.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Large scale stone masonry for public use, and organised seal estampage of international importance are associated characteristics of the era.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Amiet sees as a 'proto-royal figure,' i.e., potentially Enki, preceding the 'priest-kings' of the 4th millennium.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] In modern Turkey: Strong Anatolian polities counteract the balance of power from the Ubaid polities and dwaining Samarrans who were culturally assimilated around 4800 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Such polities include Mersin notably having a standing army circa 4300 BC, and Hamoukar, which was a major production centre in the important Obsidian trade and thus power.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] An intensive copper trade, connecting Europe with the East, is represented in Anatolia by sites at Hacilar, Beycesultan, Canhasan, Mersin Yumuktepe, Elazig Tepecik, Malatya Degirmentepe, Norşuntepe, and Istanbul Fikirtepe.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Prior environmental devastation in the previous two millennia may account for the lack of Neolithic sites in northern Turkey.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] In the Levant: Ghassulian culture thrives, immigrating from the North into the whole of the Levant circa 4400 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] With concentrated settlements and elites economically focused on copper metallurgy and trade, notably importing from Southern Jordan's vast and powerful urban polities and Bedouin-like cultures.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] This Sotira culture replaced the void of the collapse of the 6th millennium Neolithic culture in Cyprus.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Trade with Levant and external regions on an impressive scale and covering large distances starts to connect Europe with Asia on a more direct scale than before.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Obsidian found in the Chalcolithic levels at Gilat, Israel have had their origins traced via elemental analysis to three sources in Southern Anatolia: Hotamis Dağ, Göllü Dağ, and as far east as Nemrut Dağ, 500 km (310 mi) east of the other two sources.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] This is indicative of a very large trade circle reaching as far as the Northern Fertile Crescent and Anatolia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] In the Caucasus: Settlements of the 5th millennium BC in North Caucasus attest to a material culture that was related to contemporaneous archaeological complexes in the northern and western Black Sea region like the Leyla-Tepe culture (c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] These polities were immense economically, and pioneered copper metallurgy and trade.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Constant immigration from Ubadians and from Uruk herself did play economic factors as well.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Such cultural elements change and are replaced, suddenly during the latter first half of the 4th Millennium BC, and the quality of copper metallurgy declines somewhat, during the Kura–Araxes culture.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] On the other hand, the millennia long attested Shulaveri–Shomu culture showed stronger cultural connections like similar tool kits and use of red ochre, portrays intimate and centuries-old ties with the Halafians.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] In Arabia: Continuation of Ubaid economical expansion and culture(since the 6th millennium BC, circa 5500 BC) throughout Arabia, with adoption and integration but also contributions to these new political features.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Ubaid pottery of periods 2 and 3 has been documented at site H3 in Kuwait and in Dosariyah in eastern Saudi Arabia, which bordered the Persian Gulf, a major trade hub.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Significant linguistic connections are made with the precursor to the Proto-Indo European languages (circa 4500 BC), via the Eurasiatic language and parts of the Dravidian language to a prior language family during the Upper Palaeolithic.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Dravidian having multiple cultural origins and development over millennia can be considered just as influential on an international scale as the Indo European languages from the 5th millennium BC to the 1st millennium AD.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Such influence has been explored, such examples are the Elamo-Dravidian languages, a family that would have pioneered Susa, Central Mesopotamia, trade and politics within the Ubaid era.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] These Southern migrations into India contributed to parts of the Proto-Dravidian language, having multiple variants i.e., Proto-South Dravidian language based on geographical location, however the language itself is known to have largely been native to central India as well.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] This melting pot of cultures peaked from the 5th millennium BC into the 4th millennium BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Chinese civilisation advanced in this millennium with the beginnings of three noted cultures from around 5000 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] The Yangshao culture was based in the Huang He (Yellow River) basin and endured for some 2,000 years.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] It is believed that pigs were first domesticated there.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Pottery was fired in kilns dug into the ground and then painted.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] A type-site settlement for the Yangshao was established c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] 4700 BC at Banpo near modern Xi'an, Shaanxi.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Also about 5000 BC, the Hemudu culture began in eastern China with cultivation of rice, and the Majiabang culture was established on the Yangtze estuary near modern Shanghai, lasting until c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] It is estimated that the distinctive Aboriginal rock carvings near Sydney were created sometime between 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Sea levels had become relatively stabilized by the time of 4500 BC around the coastlines of Australia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] This occurred after several thousands of years of sea level rising, due to glaciers melting after the Younger Dryas event.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] This knowledge was passed down in oral history among the Aboriginal tribes of Australia as they recalled the drastic sea level rises that ended up swallowing their once lower coastlines.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Around the time of the 5th Millennium BC, there was a proliferation of stone tool, plant processing and landscape modification technologies.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Elaborate fish and eel traps involving channels up to three kilometres long were in use in western Victoria from about 6,500 years ago.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Semi-permanent collections of wooden huts on mounds also appeared in western Victoria, associated with a more systematic exploitation of new food sources in the wetlands.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] The Furneaux Group, which is a set of islands off the Northeast portion of Tasmania, had been inhabited since at least 33,000 BC, but the Aboriginal Tasmanians stopped living there permanently around the time of 4,000 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Rock art in the Northern Territory of Australia, specifically from the area of Arnhem Land is said to have a portion of its depictions dating to around 4,000 BC, which show battle scenes or skirmishes between the people in the local area.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] The art also includes animals and other ceremonial meanings.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] These scenes have been dated to up to 10,000 years old and down to 6,000 years old when painted continuously over time.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Stone points for spears and distinct stone point technology have been found dating from 5–7 thousand years ago in Australia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Many of the early stone point technologies are specifically found in the Kimberley Region of north-western Australia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Spear-launching devices, such as the woomera are believed to have entered widespread use at around this time.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] More complex structures followed during a second intensive wave onwards from 4500 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] With alignments with Sirius, Arcturus, Alpha Centauri, and the Belt of Orion.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] This suggests a great academic pursuit to investigate astronomical observations, cosmology and mathematics.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Fifth millennium alignments of stele to bright stars focussed on issues of major practical importance of the era being: cattle, water, death, earth, sun, stars and theology.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Shell mounds in these areas are highly visible, which likely aided in their identification by scholars.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Examples like Cerro de las Conchas, which dates between 5500 and 3500BC appearing to have been a sea resource collection and processing site.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] While it seems Cerro de las Conchas was only occupied seasonally, it seems likely that inland base camps were occupied year-round.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Lauricocha III: 4200 – 2500 BC (Andean preceramic V) begins.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Chiefdoms and fish gatherer-hunter societies dominate.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Lauricocha was one of the important mountain encampments at the time.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] The 5th millennium has become a start point for calendars and chronologies.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] The year 4750 BC is the retrospective startpoint for the Assyrian calendar, marking the traditional date for the foundation of Assur, some 2,000 years before it actually happened.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Another traditional date is 19 July 4241 BC, marking the supposed beginning of the Egyptian calendar, as calculated retrospectively by Eduard Meyer.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] The more likely startpoint is 19 July 2781 BC, one Sothic cycle later.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] It has generally been believed that the calendar was based on a heliacal (dawn) rising of Sirius but that view is now being questioned.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] According to the Ussher chronology, the creation of Earth happened on 22/23 October 4004 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] This chronology was the work of James Ussher, whose basis was the dates in the Old Testament of the Bible.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] He estimated that the universe was created by God at either 18:00 on the 22nd (Jewish calendar) or 09:00 on the 23rd (Ussher-Lightfoot-Chronology).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] Yet another calendar starting date in the 5th millennium is Monday, 1 January 4713 BC, the beginning of the current Julian Period, first described by Joseph Justus Scaliger in the sixteenth century.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] This Julian Period lasts 7,980 years until the year 3268 (current era) in the next millennium.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] It is a useful device for date conversions between different calendars.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/5th-millennium-bce] The date of origin has the integer value of zero in the Julian Day Count: i.e., in the Julian Calendar; the equivalent date in the Gregorian Calendar is 24 November 4714 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] The **7th millennium BC** spanned the years 7000 BC to 6001 BC (c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] It is impossible to precisely date events around this millennium, and all dates mentioned here are estimates mostly based on geological and anthropological analysis.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] Towards the end of this millennium, the islands of Great Britain, and Ireland were severed from continental Europe by rising sea levels.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] Neolithic culture and technology were established in the Near East by 7000 BC and there is increasing evidence through the millennium of its spread or introduction to Europe and the Far East.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] In most of the world, however, including north and western Europe, people still lived in scattered Palaeolithic hunter-gatherer communities.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] The Mehrgarh Chalcolithic civilization began around 7000 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] The world population is believed to have been stable and slowly increasing.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] It has been estimated that there were perhaps ten million people worldwide at the end of this millennium, growing to forty million by 5000 BC and 100 million by 1600 BC, an average growth rate of 0.027% p.a. from the beginning of the Neolithic to the Middle Bronze Age.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] Neolithic culture and technology reached modern Turkey and Greece c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] The innovations, including the introduction of farming, spread from the Middle East through Turkey and Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] There is evidence of domesticated sheep or goats, pigs, and cattle, together with grains of cultivated bread wheat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] The domestication of pigs in Eastern Europe is believed to have begun c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] The pigs may have descended from European wild boar or were probably introduced by farmers migrating from the Middle East.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] 6200 BC, of farmers from the Middle East reaching the Danube and moving into Romania and Serbia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] Farming gradually spread westward and northward over the next four millennia, finally reaching Great Britain and Scandinavia c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] 3000 BC to complete the transition of Europe from the Mesolithic to the Neolithic.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] 6500–3800 BC) began in Mesopotamia, its name derived from Tell al-'Ubaid where the first significant excavation took place.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] By the end of this millennium, Jericho had become a large agricultural settlement with some eight to ten acres within its walls.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] Kathleen Kenyon reckoned that it was home to about three thousand people.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] Construction was done using stone implements to mould clay into bricks.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] "Sheep and goats were domesticated in South West Asia, probably in the region of eastern Anatolia and northern Syria between 8000 and 7500 BC, and were part of the agricultural package that was transmitted to Greece and the Balkans during the pioneering movements in the seventh millennium.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] In the geologic time scale, the "Northgrippian" succeeded the "Greenlandian" c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] The starting point for the Northgrippian is the so-called 8.2 kiloyear event, which was an abrupt climate change lasting some four centuries in which there was a marked decrease in global temperatures, possibly caused by an influx of glacial meltwater into the North Atlantic Ocean.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] The influx is believed to be one factor in the creation of Great Britain and Ireland as islands separate from the European continent.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] 9700 BC, increasing sea levels gradually inundated Doggerland, a land bridge that linked Great Britain to Denmark and the Netherlands.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] This process began the formation of the North Sea and the English Channel.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] Further west, another low-lying land area was being flooded to form the Irish Sea and create Ireland.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] Sometime in the second half of the 7th millennium, the Storegga Slides occurred off Norway to generate a huge tsunami that completely overwhelmed Doggerland and its Mesolithic community of an estimated 5,000 hunter-gatherers.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] By about 6100 BC, Great Britain had become an island.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/7th-millennium-bce] This is one of the rarest astronomical events in the Solar System, with the next occurrence on 17 February, 7541.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The **Abbasid Caliphate** or **Abbasid Empire** was the third Islamic caliphate, ruled by the Abbasid dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The dynasty was descended from Muhammad's uncle, Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib (d.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids rose to power in 750, when the Abbasid Revolution overthrew the preceding Umayyad Caliphate, and they ruled as caliphs from their metropole in Iraq until 1258, with Baghdad as their capital for most of their history.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasid Revolution had its origins and first successes in the easterly region of Khurasan, far from the Levantine center of Umayyad influence.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids first centered their government in Kufa, Iraq, but in 762 the second caliph al-Mansur founded the city of Baghdad and made it the capital.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Baghdad became a center of science, culture, arts, and invention, ushering in what became known as the Golden Age of Islam.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] It hosted several key academic institutions, such as the House of Wisdom, as well as a multi-ethnic and multi-religious population, which made the city famous as a centre of learning across the world.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasid period was marked by the use of bureaucrats in government, including the vizier, as well as a growing inclusion of non-Arab Muslims in the *ummah* (Muslim community) and among the political elites.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The height of Abbasid power and prestige is traditionally associated with the reign of Harun al-Rashid (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] After his death, a civil war brought new divisions and was followed by significant changes to the character of the state, including the creation of a new professional army recruited mainly from Turkic slaves and the construction of a new capital, Samarra, in 836.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The 9th century also saw many provinces becoming increasingly autonomous, giving rise to local dynasties that controlled different regions of the empire, such as the Aghlabids, Tahirids, Samanids, Saffarids, and Tulunids.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] After a period of turmoil in the 860s, the caliphate regained some stability and its seat returned to Baghdad in 892.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] During the 10th century, the caliphs were reduced to mere figureheads, with real political and military power resting in the hands of the Iranian Buyids and the Seljuq Turks, who took control of Baghdad in 945 and 1055, respectively.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids eventually regained control of Iraq during the reign of Caliph al-Muqtafi (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 1136–1160) and extended their rule into Iran during the reign of Caliph al-Nasir (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This revival ended in 1258 with the sack of Baghdad by the Mongols under Hulagu Khan and the execution of Caliph al-Musta'sim, which marked the effective end of the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] A surviving branch of the Abbasid dynasty was formally reinstated in 1261 by the Mamluk sultans in Cairo, but it lacked any political power.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The dynasty continued to claim symbolic authority until the Ottoman conquest of Egypt in 1517, the last Abbasid caliph being al-Mutawakkil III.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasid caliphs descended from Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib, one of the youngest uncles of Muhammad and of the same Banu Hashim clan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This family relation to Muhammad made them appealing to those who were discontented with the rule of the Umayyad caliphs (661–750), who did not descend from the same family.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Over the course of their rule, the Umayyads even suppressed several rebellions that attempted to bring other members of Muhammad's family to power.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] One of the claims that the Abbasids made in the early years of their political movement was that Abu Hashim, the son of Muhammad ibn al-Hanafiyya and grandson of Ali, had formally transferred the Imamate (*imāmah*) to Muhammad ibn Ali (the great-grandson of Abbas) and thus to the Abbasid family.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Muhammad ibn Ali began to campaign in Persia for the return of power to the family of Muhammad, the Hashemites, in the context of the reign of Umar II.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Later, after they had attained power and needed to broaden their support among Muslims, the Abbasids supplemented this claim with other claims to justify their legitimacy.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids also distinguished themselves from the Umayyads by attacking their moral character and administration in general.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids also appealed to non-Arab Muslims, known as *mawali*, who remained outside the kinship-based society of the Arabs and were perceived as a lower class within the Umayyad empire.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] According to Ira Lapidus, "The Abbasid revolt was supported largely by Arabs, mainly the aggrieved settlers of Merv with the addition of the Yemeni faction and their Mawali".
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] During the reign of Marwan II, this opposition culminated in the rebellion of Ibrahim al-Imam, the fourth in descent from Abbas.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Supported by the province of Khurasan (eastern Iran), even though the governor opposed them, and the Shi'i Arabs, he achieved considerable success, but was captured and died in prison in 749.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] On 9 June 747 (15 Ramadan AH 129), Abu Muslim, rising from Khurasan, successfully initiated an open revolt against Umayyad rule, which was carried out under the sign of the Black Standard.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Close to 10,000 soldiers were under Abu Muslim's command when the hostilities officially began in Merv.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] General Qahtaba followed the fleeing governor Nasr ibn Sayyar west defeating the Umayyads at the Battle of Gorgan, the Battle of Nahavand and finally in the Battle of Karbala, all in the year 748.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Ibrahim was captured by Marwan and was killed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The quarrel was taken up by Ibrahim's brother Abdallah, known by the name of Abu al-'Abbas al-Saffah, who defeated the Umayyads in 750 in the battle near the Great Zab river and was subsequently proclaimed caliph.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] After this loss, Marwan fled to Egypt, where he was subsequently killed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The remainder of his family, barring one male, were also eliminated.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 750–754) was spent consolidating Abbasid rule over the Muslim community.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Soon after the victory of 750, Abu Muslim sent forces to Central Asia to confront an army from Tang China led by Gao Xianzhi.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Gao Xianzhi and his army were defeated in 751 at the Battle of Talas, near present-day Tashkent, by the Abbasid army under Ziyad ibn Salih.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This defeat marked the end of Tang influence in Transoxiana and halted Tang westward expansion.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids then consolidated their rule in Transoxania.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Elsewhere, the Abbasids focused on putting down numerous rebellions in Syria and Iraq.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Byzantines conducted raids during these early distractions.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] One of the first major changes effected by Abbasid rule was the move of the caliphate's center of power from Syria to Iraq.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This was closer to the Persian *mawali* support base of the Abbasids and the move addressed their demand for reduced Arab dominance in the empire.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] However, no definitive capital was yet selected.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In these early Abbasid years, Kufa generally served as the administrative capital, but the caliphs were wary of the Alid sympathies in the city and did not always reside here.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 752, al-Saffah built a new city called al-Hashimiyya, at an uncertain location, most likely near Kufa.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Later that same year, he moved to Anbar, where he built a new settlement for his Khurasani soldiers and a palace for himself.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] It was al-Saffah's successor, Abu Ja'far al-Mansur (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 754–775) who firmly consolidated Abbasid rule and faced down internal challenges.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] His uncle, Abdallah ibn Ali, the victor over the Umayyads at the Battle of the Zab, was the most serious potential rival for leadership and al-Mansur sent Abu Muslim, the Khurasani revolutionary commander, against him in 754.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] After Abu Muslim successfully defeated him, al-Mansur then turned to eliminate Abu Muslim himself.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] He arranged to have him arrested and executed in 755.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] On the western frontier, the Abbasids were unable to re-assert caliphal control over the western and central Maghreb, which the Umayyads had lost in the 740s.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] One member of the Umayyad dynasty, Abd ar-Rahman, also managed to escape the purge of his family and established independent rule in al-Andalus (present-day Spain and Portugal) in 756, founding the Umayyad emirate of Córdoba.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 756, al-Mansur had also sent over 4,000 Arab mercenaries to assist the Tang dynasty against the rebel leader An Lushan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids, or "Black Flags" as they were commonly called, were known in Tang dynasty chronicles as the *hēiyī Dàshí*, "The Black-robed Tazi" (黑衣大食) ("Tazi" being a borrowing from Persian *Tāzī*, the word for "Arab").
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Later, Caliph Harun al-Rashid sent embassies to China and established good relations with the Tang emperors.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] After the war, these embassies remained in China and al-Rashid established an alliance with China.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Several embassies from the Abbasid caliphs to the Chinese court have been recorded in the *Old Book of Tang*, the most important being those of al-Saffah, al-Mansur, and Harun al-Rashid.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 762, al-Mansur suppressed a rebellion in the Hejaz led by al-Nafs al-Zakiyya, a descendant from Ali ibn Abi Talib, whose challenge to the Abbasid claim to leadership was based on his Alid lineage and thus presented a serious political threat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] He was defeated by an Abbasid army led by Isa ibn Musa.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] It was after this victory, in 762, that al-Mansur finally established a proper Abbasid capital, Baghdad – officially called *Madinat al-Salam* ('City of Peace') – located on the Tigris River, near the former ancient capital city of Ctesiphon.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Prior to this, he had continued to consider multiple sites for a capital, including al-Hashimiyya, which he used as a capital for a while, and al-Rumiyya (near the ruins of Ctesiphon), which he used for a few months.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Various other sites in the region also appear to have served as "capitals" under either al-Saffah or al-Mansur prior to the founding of Baghdad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Al-Mansur centralised the judicial administration and, later, Harun al-Rashid established the institution of Great Qadi to oversee it.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Umayyad empire was mostly Arab; however, the Abbasids progressively became made up of more and more converted Muslims in which the Arabs were only one of many ethnicities.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids had depended heavily on the support of Persians in their overthrow of the Umayyads.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Al-Mansur welcomed non-Arab Muslims to his court.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] While this helped integrate Arab and Persian cultures, it alienated many of their Arab supporters, particularly the Khurasani Arabs who had supported them in their battles against the Umayyads.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] It was also during this early period of the dynasty, in particular during the rule of al-Mansur, Harun al-Rashid, and al-Ma'mun, that its reputation and power were created.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The position of *wazir* (vizier) developed in this period.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] It was initially akin to a secretary, but under the tenure of the Barmakids, an Iranian family close to the Abbasids, the position became powerful and Harun al-Rashid delegated state affairs to them for many years.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This resulted in a more ceremonial role for many Abbasid caliphs compared with caliphal rule under the Umayyads; the viziers began to exert greater influence, and the role of the caliph's aristocracy was slowly replaced by a Barmakid bureaucracy.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] At the western end of the empire, Harun al-Rashid agreed to grant the province of Ifriqiya (centered in present-day Tunisia) as a hereditary emirate to Ibrahim ibn al-Aghlab, who founded the Aghlabid dynasty there.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 786–809), the Abbasid Empire reached its peak.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 775–785), restarted the fighting with the Byzantines, and his sons continued the conflict until Empress Irene pushed for peace.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] After several years of peace, Nikephoros I broke the treaty, then fended off multiple incursions during the first decade of the 9th century.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] These Abbasid attacks pushed into the Taurus Mountains, culminating with a victory at the Battle of Krasos and the massive invasion of 806, led by al-Rashid himself.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Harun al-Rashid's navy also proved successful, taking Cyprus.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Al-Rashid then focused on the rebellion of Rafi ibn al-Layth in Khurasan and died while there.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Domestically, al-Rashid pursued policies similar to those of his father al-Mahdi.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] He released many of the Umayyads and Alids his brother al-Hadi (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 785–786) had imprisoned and declared amnesty for all political groups of the Quraysh.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] While Baghdad remained the official capital, al-Rashid chose to reside in Raqqa from 796 until the end of his reign.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 802, he established an unusual succession plan which decreed that his son al-Amin would inherit the title of Caliph and have control of Iraq and the western empire while his other son al-Ma'mun would rule Khurasan and most eastern parts of the empire.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 803, he turned on and imprisoned or killed most of the Barmakids, who had wielded administrative power on his behalf.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The reasons for this sudden and ruthless move remain unclear and have been the subject of much discussion by contemporary writers and later historians.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Al-Rashid's decision to split the succession proved to be damaging to the longevity of the empire.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] After his death in 809, his succession pact eventually collapsed and the empire was split by a civil war between al-Amin in Iraq and al-Ma'mun in Khurasan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This ended with a successful siege of Baghdad by al-Ma'mun's forces.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] When the city fell in 813, al-Amin was captured and executed on the orders of al-Ma'mun's general, Tahir ibn Husayn.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This marked the first time that an Abbasid ruler was publicly executed and it irrevocably damaged the prestige of the caliphate.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Al-Ma'mun became caliph and ruled until his death in 833.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] He initially ruled the empire from his established base in Merv, Khurasan, where his main support was found, but this prolonged the discontent and instability in Iraq and triggered further fighting in the years following his victory.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 817, he officially declared an Alid, 'Ali al-Rida, as his heir, instead of an Abbasid family member, perhaps hoping to promote Muslim unity, but the move backfired.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Eventually, he was compelled to step back from these policies and move his court to Baghdad, where he arrived in August 819.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] After this, the rest of his reign was relatively peaceful.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Exceptions included a rebellion in Azerbaijan by the Khurramites, supported by the Byzantines, which continued until 837.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] He also repulsed a Byzantine attack on Syria around 829, followed by counter-attacks into Anatolia, and suppressed a rebellion in Egypt in 832.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The later years of al-Ma'mun's reign are known for his intellectual interests and patronage.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The so-called "translation movement" — the state-sponsored translation of scientific and literary works of antiquity into Arabic — that had begun under his predecessors was pushed even further during this time and al-Ma'mun shifted its focus to ancient Greek works of science and philosophy.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In matters of religion, his interest in philosophy spurred him to endorse Mu'tazilism, the rationalist school of Islamic thought.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Under its influence, he officially endorsed the doctrine of createdness of the Qur'an in 827.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 833, he went further and forcibly imposed it on the *ulama*, the Sunni religious scholars.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This controversial policy, known as the *Mihna*, was eventually abandoned in 848.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Ultimately, it failed to convince the Sunni *ulama* and instead contributed to the emergence of the latter as a more cohesive social class whose views and interests did not always align with the caliph.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Following the civil war between al-Amin and al-Ma'mun, the traditional mainstay of the Abbasid army, the *Khurasaniyya* and *'Abna al-dawla*, were no longer seen as reliable and the caliphs sought to recruit a new type of army whose loyalty could be better assured.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This process began under al-Ma'mun but it is his brother and successor, al-Mu'tasim (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 833–842), who is known for its more radical implementation.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Soldiers were recruited from several new sources, but the most important, especially under al-Mu'tasim, were the group referred to by Arabic chronicles as "Turks" (*atrāk*), who appear to have been mainly Turkic people from Central Asia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Some modern scholars refer to them as Mamluks, marking them as the antecedent of the later slave-soldiers known by that term, but their exact legal status has been a subject of scholarly debate.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Many, perhaps the majority, were originally purchased or captured slaves, but they were paid regular salaries and thus likely manumitted.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In any case, these outsiders did not have political ties among the traditional elites and thus their loyalty was to the caliph alone.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] These troops were likely the first standing army of the caliphate and provided the caliph with a strong base of military support.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] However, the influx of new foreign troops into the capital created tensions with its inhabitants and with older elites.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This was one of the main reasons why, in 836, al-Mu'tasim decided to found a new capital, Samarra, on an open site to the north of Baghdad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The new capital housed the caliph's army, allowed for the unhindered construction of massive new palaces, and became the focus of an even more elaborate courtly culture.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Al-Mu'tasim's reign marked the end of the strong caliphs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] He strengthened his personal army with the Mamluks and promptly restarted the war with the Byzantines.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Though his attempt to seize Constantinople failed when his fleet was destroyed by a storm, his military excursions were generally successful, culminating with a resounding victory in the Sack of Amorium.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] From the ninth century onward, the Abbasids found they could no longer keep together a centralized polity from Baghdad, which had grown larger than that of Rome.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] As mentioned, Harun al-Rashid had already granted the province of Ifriqiya to the Aghlabids, who ruled this region as an autonomous vassal state until its fall to the Fatimids in 909.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In al-Ma'mun's reign, Tahir ibn Husayn (al-Ma'mun's general in the civil war) was appointed viceroy of Iran and most of the eastern regions of the empire from 821 onward.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] His descendants, the Tahirids, continued to govern in this position with significant autonomy until 873, although they remained loyal to the caliph and used only the title of *amir*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] From their capital at Nishapur, they were important patrons of Arabic literature and Sunni religious scholarship, in addition to making major improvements to agriculture.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In Transoxiana, the Persian Samanids of Bukhara and Samarkand ruled as local governors, initially under the Tahirids.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] They oversaw the development of the region's cities into major trade centers, profiting from long-distance trade between China, Central Asia, Eastern Europe, and the Middle East.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 847–861) was characterized by the caliph's extravagant spending, his attempts to further consolidate power within the state, and his replacement of the *Mihna* policy with support for more orthodox Sunni scholars, in particular the Hanbali school.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 853, the Byzantines sacked Damietta in Egypt, and the caliph responded by sending troops into Anatolia, who sacked and marauded until they were eventually annihilated in 863.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Al-Mutawakkil's lifestyle and spending weakened his support among the military.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 861, he was murdered at a party by a group of Turkish soldiers.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This was the first time the Abbasid military intervened so directly and violently at court and it set a precedent for further coups.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The following period, sometimes known as the "Anarchy at Samarra" (861–870), saw four different caliphs come and go.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] While they each attempted to reassert their authority, they were at the mercy of military and political factions.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Tax collection lapsed and, along with al-Mutawakkil's previous spending, this left the state short on funds, which exacerbated the infighting.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 865, the Turkish soldiers of Samarra even besieged Baghdad to overthrow the caliph al-Musta'in and, when the city fell the following year, they replaced him with al-Mu'tazz.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The latter was overthrown by the same faction in 869 and replaced by al-Muhtadi, who was similarly overthrown in 870.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Al-Muhtadi was succeeded by al-Mu'tamid, who was finally able to restore some order, in large part thanks to the help of his brother al-Muwaffaq, who kept the military under control and ran most government affairs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The restoration was hampered by the Zanj rebellion, which erupted in 869 and threatened the center of Abbasid control in Iraq.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This major threat was not brought under control until a determined campaign was launched in 879.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] By the 870s, Egypt became autonomous under Ahmad ibn Tulun and his Tulunid successors, though they continued to acknowledge the caliph and generally sent tribute to Baghdad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] For a time, they even controlled Syria and parts of the Jazira (Upper Mesopotamia).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 882, the caliph al-Mu'tamid even tried to move his residence to Egypt at Ibn Tulun's invitation, though this move was aborted by the intervention of al-Muwaffaq.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In the east, the Saffarids were former soldiers in the Abbasid army who were stationed in Sistan and remained there as local strongmen.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] They began to challenge the Tahirids from 854 onward and in 873 they captured Nishapur, ending Tahirid rule.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] They marched on Baghdad in 876 but were defeated by al-Muwaffaq.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The two sides were forced to come to terms and the Abbasids allowed the Saffarids to rule over Sistan, Fars, Kirman, and Khurasan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 898, al-Mu'tadid set the Saffarids and Samanids against each other by formally endorsing a Saffarid claim over Transoxiana, the Samanid domain.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Samanids emerged triumphant in battle and were able to expand their control thenceforth to Khurasan, while the Saffarids were contained further south.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Samanids never threatened Iraq or western Iran, but they were also not as close to the caliphs as their Tahirid predecessors and in practice they were almost entirely independent of Baghdad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] They became even greater patrons of religion and the arts than the Tahirids.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] They still maintained an orthodox Sunni ideology but they differed from their predecessors by promoting the Persian language.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] There was a brief Abbasid political and military revival at the end of the 9th century, especially under the policies of caliphs al-Mu'tadid (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Under al-Mu'tadid, the capital was moved from Samarra back to Baghdad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Incursions by the Qarmatians and allied Bedouin tribes posed a serious threat from 899 onwards, but the Abbasid army, led by Muhammad ibn Sulayman, won a reprieve against them in 904 and 907.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 905, the same general invaded Egypt and overthrew the weakened Tulunids, re-establishing Abbasid control to the west.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] By the time caliph al-Muktafi died in 908, the Abbasid revival was at its peak and a strong centralized state was in place again.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] After his death, however, the state became dominated by feuding bureaucrats.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 908–932), the Abbasid court continued to project power and wealth publicly but the politics and financial policies of the time compromised the caliphate's sustainability in the long-term.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] It was in this period that the practice of giving out *iqta*s (fiefs in the form of tax farms) as favours began, which had the effect of reducing the caliphate's own tax revenues.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 909, North Africa was lost to the Fatimid dynasty, an Isma'ili Shia sect tracing its roots to Muhammad's daughter Fatima.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Fatimids took control of Ifriqiya from the Aghlabids and eventually conquered Egypt in 969, where they established their capital, Cairo, near Fustat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] By the end of the century, they were one of the main political and ideological challenges to Sunni Islam and the Abbasids, contesting the Abbasids for the titular authority of the Islamic *ummah*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The challenge of the Fatimid Caliphate only ended with their downfall in the 12th century.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 934–941), Baghdad's authority declined further as local governors refused to send payments to the capital.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Ikhshidids ruled Egypt and Syria autonomously prior to the Fatimid takeover.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Even in Iraq, many governors refused to obey and the caliph was unable to send armies against them.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Al-Radi was forced to invite the governor of Wasit, Muhammad ibn Ra'iq, to take over the administration under the newly created position of *amir al-umara* ("Commander of Commanders").
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Ibn Ra'iq disbanded the salaried army of the caliph and reduced much of the government's bureaucratic infrastructure, including the traditional vizierate, thus removing much of the Abbasid state's basis for power.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] He was overthrown in 938 and the following years were bogged down in political turmoil.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Al-Mustakfi had a short reign from 944 to 946, and it was during this period that the Persian faction known as the Buyids from Daylam swept into power and assumed control over the bureaucracy in Baghdad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] According to the history of Miskawayh, they began distributing *iqta*s to their supporters.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This period of localized secular control was to last nearly 100 years.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Mahmud of Ghazni took the title of sultan, as opposed to the *amir* that had been in more common usage, signifying the Ghaznavid Empire's independence from caliphal authority, despite Mahmud's ostentatious displays of Sunni orthodoxy and ritual submission to the caliph.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In the 11th century, the loss of respect for the caliphs continued, as some Islamic rulers no longer mentioned the caliph's name in the Friday *khutba*, or struck it off their coinage.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Despite the power of the Buyid amirs, the Abbasids retained a highly ritualized court in Baghdad, as described by the Buyid bureaucrat Hilal al-Sabi', and they retained a certain influence over Baghdad as well as religious life.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] As Buyid power waned with the rule of Baha' al-Daula, the caliphate was able to regain some measure of strength.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The caliph al-Qadir, for example, led the ideological struggle against the Shia with writings such as the *Baghdad Manifesto*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The caliphs kept order in Baghdad itself, attempting to prevent the outbreak of *fitna*s in the capital, often contending with the *ayyarun*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] With the Buyid dynasty on the wane, a vacuum was created that was eventually filled by the dynasty of Oghuz Turks known as the Seljuqs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] By 1055, the Seljuqs had wrested control from the Buyids and Abbasids, and took temporal power.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] When the amir and former slave Basasiri took up the Shia Fatimid banner in Baghdad in 1056–57, the caliph al-Qa'im was unable to defeat him without outside help.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Toghril Beg, the Seljuq sultan, restored Baghdad to Sunni rule and took Iraq for his dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Once again, the Abbasids were forced to deal with a military power that they could not match, though the Abbasid caliph remained the titular head of the Islamic community.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The succeeding sultans Alp Arslan and Malikshah, as well as their vizier Nizam al-Mulk, took up residence in Persia, but held power over the Abbasids in Baghdad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] When the dynasty began to weaken in the 12th century, the Abbasids gained greater independence once again.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 1118–1135) was the first caliph to build an army and to lead it in battle since the 10th century.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] He recruited Kurdish and Arab Bedouin tribes and re-fortified Baghdad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] His first concern was not the Seljuks but the Mazyadids of Hilla in central Iraq, whom he met in battle in 1123.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] His bid for independence was ultimately unsuccessful, as he was defeated by a Seljuk army in 1135 and assassinated soon after.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 1136–1160), a new caliphal state began to emerge with the help of his vizier Ibn Hubayra.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Ibn Hubayra concentrated on reasserting authority in Iraq while the Seljuk Empire deteriorated.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids successfully defended Baghdad against the Seljuqs in the siege of 1157 and then conquered their Mazyadid enemies in Hilla in 1162.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] By the end of al-Muqtafi's reign, Baghdad controlled a state stretching from Basra in the south to the edges of Mosul in the north.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] After over two hundred years of Abbasid subjection to foreign dynasties, Caliph al-Mustanjid (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 1160–1170) formally declared independence from the Seljuk sultans in 1165, when he dropped their names from Abbasid coinage.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Initially, the caliphs were still vulnerable to the power of the viziers, but al-Mustadi (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 1170–1180) was able to further rally some support from the Baghdad public as well as symbolic support abroad from the Ayyubid sultan Saladin and the Rum Seljuk sultan Kilij Arslan II.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 1180–1225) marked a definitive shift in late Abbasid power.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] He reinvigorated public displays of caliphal prestige, removed officials who were too powerful, engaged in diplomacy with regions beyond Iraq, and extended his control over former Seljuk territories in western Iran — including Isfahan, Hamadan, Qazvin and Zanjan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] He sought to build up his influence among Muslim rulers abroad largely through the Sufi-inspired *futuwwa* brotherhood that he headed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] 1226–1242), the Abbasid state achieved significant stability and many of the same policies continued.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] He built the Mustansiriyya Madrasa, inaugurated in 1234, the first madrasa to teach all four Sunni *maddhab*s (schools of jurisprudence) and the first madrasa commissioned by an Abbasid caliph.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 1206, Genghis Khan established a powerful dynasty among the Mongols of Central Asia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] During the 13th century, this Mongol Empire conquered most of the Eurasian land mass, including both China in the east and much of the old Islamic caliphate and the Kievan Rus' in the west.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 1252, Hulagu Khan, a grandson of Genghis Khan and brother of the new Mongol ruler, Möngke Khan, was placed in charge of a new western campaign to the Middle East that would culminate in the conquest of Baghdad in 1258.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In the years leading up the Mongol invasion, Baghdad's strength was sapped by political rivalries, sectarian tensions between Sunnis and Shias, and damaging floods.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 1257, after destroying the Assassins in Iran, Hulagu wrote to the Abbasid caliph, al-Musta'sim, demanding his submission.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The caliph refused, with Hulagu's status as a non-Muslim (unlike the earlier Buyids and Seljuks) likely a factor.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] There followed months of diplomacy, during which the Mongols may have been informed of Baghdad's weakness by correspondence with the caliph's vizier, Ibn al-Alqami, a Shia who was later accused of colluding with them.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Mongols began their siege of the city on 29 January 1258.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] On 10 February, al-Musta'sim agreed to meet with Hulagu, who demanded that the caliph order the defenders to stand down and come out of the city in exchange for mercy.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The caliph complied, but the Mongols slaughtered the population and then began the sack of the city on 13 February.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Contemporary accounts describe destruction, looting, rape, and killing on a massive scale over many days, with hundreds of thousands killed and the city reduced to near-empty ruins, though some, like the Christian and Shia communities, were spared.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Mongols feared rumours that a supernatural disaster would strike if the blood of al-Musta'sim, a direct descendant of Muhammad's uncle and part of a dynasty that had reigned for five centuries, was spilled.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] As a precaution and in accordance with a Mongol taboo against spilling royal blood, Hulagu had al-Musta'sim wrapped in a carpet and trampled to death by horses on 20 February 1258.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The caliph's immediate family was also executed, with the lone exceptions of his youngest son who was sent to Mongolia and a daughter who became a slave in the harem of Hulagu.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The fall of Baghdad marked the effective end of the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] It made a deep impression on contemporary and later writers both inside and outside the Muslim world, some of whom created legendary stories about the last caliph's demise.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] It is also traditionally seen as the approximate end to the "classical age" or "golden age" of Islamic civilization.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The events brought profound geopolitical changes to the traditional lands of the Islamic caliphate, with Iraq, Iran, and most of the eastern lands falling under Mongol control while other Muslim rulers retained the lands to the west.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Mongol expansion further west was eventually halted by the Mamluks of Egypt at the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260, followed by the conflict between the Ilkhanids (Hulagu and his successors) and their Golden Horde rivals, which diverted Mongol attention.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Prior to the Mongol invasion, the later Ayyubid sultans of Egypt had built up an army recruited from slaves, the Mamluks.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] During a political and military crisis in 1250, the Mamluks seized power and established what is now known as the Mamluk Sultanate.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Following the devastation of Baghdad in 1258 and in an effort to secure political legitimacy for the new regime in Egypt, the Mamluk ruler Baybars invited a surviving member of the Abbasid family to establish himself in Cairo in 1260–1261.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The new caliph was al-Mustansir II, a brother of the former caliph al-Mustansir.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 1262, he disappeared while leading a small army in an attempt to recapture Baghdad from the Mongols.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Baybars subsequently replaced him with al-Hakim I, another Abbasid family member who had just been proclaimed in Aleppo.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Thereafter, the Abbasid caliphs in Cairo continued to exist as a strictly ceremonial but nonetheless important institution within the Mamluk Sultanate, conferring significant prestige on the Mamluks.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] It continued to be relevant even to other Muslim rulers until the 14th century; for example, the sultans of Delhi, the Muzaffarid sultan Muhammad, the Jalayirid sultan Ahmad, and the Ottoman sultan Bayezid I all sought diplomas of investiture from the caliph or declared nominal allegiance to him.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Caliph al-Musta'in even managed to reign as sultan in Cairo for a brief six months in 1412.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] During the 15th century, however, the institution of the caliph declined in significance.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The last Abbasid caliph in Cairo was al-Mutawakkil III, who was in place when the Ottoman sultan Selim I defeated the Mamluks in 1516 and conquered Egypt in 1517, ending the Mamluk Sultanate.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Selim I met with al-Mutawakkil III in Aleppo in 1516, prior to marching into Egypt, and the caliph was then sent to the Ottoman capital of Constantinople (present-day Istanbul), ending the Abbasid caliphate definitively.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids themselves slipped into historical obscurity after this.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The idea of a "caliphate" subsequently became an ambiguous concept that was occasionally revisited by later Muslim rulers and intellectuals for political or religious reasons.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Ottoman sultans, who were thenceforth the most powerful Muslim rulers in western Asia and the Mediterranean, did not use the title of "caliph" at all before the mid-16th century and only did so vaguely and inconsistently afterwards.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The claim that al-Mutawakkil III "transferred" the office of the caliph to the Ottoman sultan during their meeting in Aleppo is a legend that was elaborated in the 19th century and is not corroborated by contemporary accounts.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasid historical period lasting to the Mongol conquest of Baghdad in 1258 CE is considered the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Islamic Golden Age was inaugurated by the middle of the 8th century by the ascension of the Abbasid Caliphate and the transfer of the capital from Damascus to Baghdad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids were influenced by the Qur'anic injunctions and hadith, such as "the ink of a scholar is more holy than the blood of a martyr", stressing the value of knowledge.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Many classic works of antiquity that would otherwise have been lost were translated into Arabic and Persian and later in turn translated into Turkish, Hebrew and Latin.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] During this period the Muslim world was a cauldron of cultures which collected, synthesized and significantly advanced the knowledge gained from the Roman, Chinese, Indian, Persian, Egyptian, North African, Ancient Greek and Medieval Greek civilizations.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Abbasid literary culture in Iraq reflects long-term Mesopotamian narrative continuities, particularly traditions centered on heroic figures and on barriers separating chaos and order.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Core motifs associated with the Epic of Gilgamesh, mediated through the Alexander Romance, including journeys to the world's limits and the containment of chaos, persisted across religious and political change and continued to circulate in late antique Iraq.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Babylonian Talmud, composed by Iraq-based rabbis, preserves parallel traditions concerning Gog and Magog and the imagined edges of the world that confine agents of chaos.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Together, these traditions situate elements of Abbasid literature within a Mesopotamian narrative continuum.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The best-known fiction from the Islamic world is *One Thousand and One Nights*, a collection of fantastical folk tales, legends and parables compiled primarily during the Abbasid era.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The collection is recorded as having originated from an Arabic translation of a Sassanian-era Persian prototype, with likely origins in Indian literary traditions.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Stories from Arabic, Persian, Mesopotamian, and Egyptian folklore and literature were later incorporated.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The epic is believed to have taken shape in the 10th century and reached its final form by the 14th century; the number and type of tales have varied from one manuscript to another.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] All Arabian fantasy tales were often called "Arabian Nights" when translated into English, regardless of whether they appeared in *The Book of One Thousand and One Nights*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This epic has been influential in the West since it was translated in the 18th century, first by Antoine Galland.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Many imitations were written, especially in France.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Various characters from this epic have themselves become cultural icons in Western culture, such as Aladdin, Sinbad and Ali Baba.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] A famous example of Islamic poetry on romance was *Layla and Majnun*, an originally Arabic story which was further developed by Iranian, Azerbaijani and other poets in the Persian, Azerbaijani, and Turkish languages.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] It is a tragic story of undying love much like the later *Romeo and Juliet*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Arabic poetry reached its greatest height in the Abbasid era, especially before the loss of central authority and the rise of the Persianate dynasties.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Writers like Abu Tammam and Abu Nuwas were closely connected to the caliphal court in Baghdad during the early 9th century, while others such as al-Mutanabbi received their patronage from regional courts.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Under Harun al-Rashid, Baghdad was renowned for its bookstores, which proliferated after the making of paper was introduced.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Chinese papermakers had been among those taken prisoner by the Arabs at the Battle of Talas in 751.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] As prisoners of war, they were dispatched to Samarkand, where they helped set up the first Arab paper mill.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In time, paper replaced parchment as the medium for writing, and the production of books greatly increased.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] These events had an academic and societal impact that could be broadly compared to the introduction of the printing press in the West.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Paper aided in communication and record-keeping, it also brought a new sophistication and complexity to businesses, banking, and the civil service.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In 794, Jafa al-Barmak built the first paper mill in Baghdad, and from there the technology circulated.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Harun required that paper be employed in government dealings, since something recorded on paper could not easily be changed or removed, and eventually, an entire street in Baghdad's business district was dedicated to selling paper and books.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] One of the common definitions for "Islamic philosophy" is "the style of philosophy produced within the framework of Islamic culture".
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Islamic philosophy, in this definition is neither necessarily concerned with religious issues, nor is exclusively produced by Muslims.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Their works on Aristotle were a key step in the transmission of learning from ancient Greeks to the Islamic world and the West.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] They often corrected the philosopher, encouraging a lively debate in the spirit of ijtihad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] They also wrote influential original philosophical works, and their thinking was incorporated into Christian philosophy during the Middle Ages, notably by Thomas Aquinas.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Three speculative thinkers, al-Kindi, al-Farabi, and Avicenna, combined Aristotelianism and Neoplatonism with other ideas introduced through Islam, and Avicennism was later established as a result.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Other influential Abbasid philosophers include al-Jahiz, and Ibn al-Haytham (Alhacen).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] As power shifted from the Umayyads to the Abbasids, the architectural styles changed also, from Greco-Roman tradition (which features elements of Hellenistic and Roman representative style) to Eastern tradition which retained their independent architectural traditions from Mesopotamia and Persia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] A defining characteristic of Abbasid architecture in Iraq was the extensive use of stucco and plaster decoration, particularly in interior spaces.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The limited availability of high-quality building stone in Abbasid Iraq contributed to the widespread use of stucco and other malleable materials, which were well suited to repetitive and abstract ornamental decoration.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] At Samarra, these conditions enabled the emergence of a standardized decorative vocabulary that departed from Late Antique naturalism and proved influential well beyond Iraq.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Color also played an important role, particularly the use of blue pigments to enhance stucco and painted surfaces, intensifying abstraction and, in some contexts, carrying protective or apotropaic associations.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Abbasid architecture was particularly influenced by Sasanian architecture, which in turn featured elements present since ancient Mesopotamia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The Christian styles evolved into a style based more on the Sasanian Empire, utilizing mud bricks and baked bricks with carved stucco.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Other architectural innovations and styles were few, such as the four-centered arch, and a dome erected on squinches.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Unfortunately, much was lost due to the ephemeral nature of the stucco and luster tiles.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Another major development was the creation or vast enlargement of cities as they were turned into the capital of the empire, beginning with the creation of Baghdad in 762, which was planned as a walled city with four gates, and a mosque and palace in the center.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Al-Mansur, who was responsible for the creation of Baghdad, also planned the city of Raqqa, along the Euphrates.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Finally, in 836, al-Mu'tasim moved the capital to a new site that he created along the Tigris, called Samarra.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] This city saw 60 years of work, with race-courses and game preserves to add to the atmosphere.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Due to the dry remote nature of the environment, some of the palaces built in this era were isolated havens.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Al-Ukhaidir Fortress is a fine example of this type of building, which has stables, living quarters, and a mosque, all surrounding inner courtyards.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Iraq only has one surviving mausoleum from this era, in Samarra: an octagonal domed structure known as the *Qubbat al-Sulaibiyya*, which is the first known monumental tomb in Islamic architecture and may be the final resting place of al-Muntasir.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Baghdad, the epicenter of the empire, was originally organized in a circular fashion next to the Tigris River, with massive brick walls being constructed in successive rings around the core by a workforce of 100,000 with four huge gates (named Kufa, Basra, Khurasan and Syria).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The central enclosure of the city contained Mansur's palace of 360,000 square feet (33,000 m2) in area and the great mosque of Baghdad, encompassing 90,000 square feet (8,400 m2).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Travel across the Tigris and the network of waterways allowing the drainage of the Euphrates into the Tigris was facilitated by bridges and canals servicing the population.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Outside the Abbasid heartlands, architecture was still influenced by the capital.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In present-day Tunisia, the Great Mosque of Kairouan was founded under the Umayyad dynasty but completely rebuilt in the 9th century under the patronage of the Aghlabids, vassals of the Abbasids.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The styles utilized were mainly Abbasid.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] In Egypt, Ahmad Ibn Tulun commissioned the Ibn Tulun Mosque, completed in 879, that is based on the style of Samarra and is now one of the best-preserved Abbasid-style mosques from this period.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The establishment of Abbasid power based in Iraq, rather than Syria, resulted in a cultural and artistic development influenced not only by the Mediterranean and Middle Eastern traditions but also by connections further afield with India, Central Asia, and China.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] The importation of Chinese ceramics elicited local imitations but also stirred innovations in local production.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Abbasid ceramics became a more important art form with greater emphasis on decoration.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] A major innovation was the emergence of monochrome and polychrome lustreware, a technical achievement that had an important impact on the wider development of Islamic ceramics.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Glassware also became a more important art form and was likely the origin of the lustre technique that was introduced into ceramics.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Few textiles have survived but the production of *tiraz*, textiles with royal inscriptions, is well attested.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Another major art form was calligraphy and manuscript production.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] During the Abbasid period, Arabic calligraphy evolved into a more refined discipline.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Rounded Kufic script was typical and became increasingly stylized.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Parchment only allowed for a few lines of script, but from the late 8th century onward paper began to be produced.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p01] Qur'ans are the main type of book to have survived from this period.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] A number of medieval thinkers and scientists living under Islamic rule played a role in transmitting Islamic science to the Christian West.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] In addition, the period saw the recovery of much of the Alexandrian mathematical, geometric and astronomical knowledge, such as that of Euclid and Claudius Ptolemy.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] These recovered mathematical methods were later enhanced and developed by other Islamic scholars, notably by Persian scientists Al-Biruni and Abu Nasr Mansur.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Christians (particularly Nestorian Christians) contributed to the Arab Islamic Civilization during the Umayyads and the Abbasids by translating works of Greek philosophers to Syriac and afterwards to Arabic.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Nestorians played a prominent role in the formation of Arab culture, with the Academy of Gondishapur being prominent in the late Sassanid, Umayyad and early Abbasid periods.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Notably, eight generations of the Nestorian Bukhtishu family served as private doctors to caliphs and sultans between the eighth and eleventh centuries.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Algebra was significantly developed by Persian scientist Muhammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī during this time in his landmark text, *Kitab al-Jabr wa-l-Muqabala*, from which the term *algebra* is derived.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] He is thus considered to be the father of algebra by some, although the Greek mathematician Diophantus has also been given this title.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The terms *algorism* and *algorithm* are derived from the name of al-Khwarizmi, who was also responsible for introducing the Arabic numerals and Hindu–Arabic numeral system beyond the Indian subcontinent.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Arab scientist Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen) developed an early scientific method in his *Book of Optics* (1021).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The most important development of the scientific method was the use of experiments to distinguish between competing scientific theories set within a generally empirical orientation, which began among Muslim scientists.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Ibn al-Haytham's empirical proof of the intromission theory of light (that is, that light rays entered the eyes rather than being emitted by them) was particularly important.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Ibn al-Haytham was significant in the history of scientific method, particularly in his approach to experimentation, and has been referred to as the "world's first true scientist".
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Medicine in medieval Islam was an area of science that advanced particularly during the Abbasids' reign.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] During the 9th century, Baghdad contained over 800 doctors, and great discoveries in the understanding of anatomy and diseases were made.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The clinical distinction between measles and smallpox was described during this time.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Famous Persian scientist Ibn Sina (known to the West as Avicenna) produced treatises and works that summarized the vast amount of knowledge that scientists had accumulated, and was very influential through his encyclopedias, *The Canon of Medicine* and *The Book of Healing*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The work of him and many others directly influenced the research of European scientists during the Renaissance.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Astronomy in medieval Islam was advanced by Al-Battani, who improved the precision of the measurement of the precession of the Earth's axis.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The corrections made to the geocentric model by al-Battani, Averroes, Nasir al-Din al-Tusi, Mo'ayyeduddin Urdi and Ibn al-Shatir were later incorporated into the Copernican heliocentric model.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The astrolabe, though originally developed by the Greeks, was developed further by Islamic astronomers and engineers, and subsequently brought to medieval Europe.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Muslim alchemists influenced medieval European alchemists, particularly the writings attributed to Jābir ibn Hayyān (Geber).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] In technology, the Abbasids adopted papermaking from China.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The use of paper spread from China into the caliphate in the 8th century CE, arriving in al-Andalus (Islamic Spain) and then the rest of Europe in the 10th century.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] It was easier to manufacture than parchment, less likely to crack than papyrus, and could absorb ink, making it ideal for making records and copies of the Qur'an.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] "Islamic paper makers devised assembly-line methods of hand-copying manuscripts to turn out editions far larger than any available in Europe for centuries." It was from the Abbasids that the rest of the world learned to make paper from linen.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The knowledge of gunpowder was also transmitted from China via the caliphate, where the formulas for pure potassium nitrate and an explosive gunpowder effect were first developed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Advances were made in irrigation and farming, using new technology such as the windmill.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Crops such as almonds and citrus fruit were brought to Europe through al-Andalus, and sugar cultivation was gradually adopted by the Europeans.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Apart from the Nile, Tigris and Euphrates, navigable rivers were uncommon, so transport by sea was very important.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Navigational sciences were highly developed, making use of a rudimentary sextant (known as a *kamal*).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] When combined with detailed maps of the period, sailors were able to sail across oceans rather than skirt along the coast.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Abbasid sailors were also responsible for reintroducing large three masted merchant vessels to the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The name *caravel* may derive from an earlier Arab ship known as the *qārib*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Arab merchants dominated trade in the Indian Ocean until the arrival of the Portuguese in the 16th century.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Hormuz was an important center for this trade.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] There was also a dense network of trade routes in the Mediterranean, along which Muslim countries traded with each other and with European powers such as Venice or Genoa.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The Silk Road crossing Central Asia passed through the Abbasid caliphate between China and Europe.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Engineers in the Abbasid caliphate made a number of innovative industrial uses of hydropower, and early industrial uses of tidal power, wind power, and petroleum (notably by distillation into kerosene).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The industrial uses of watermills in the Islamic world date back to the 7th century, while horizontal-wheeled and vertical-wheeled water mills were both in widespread use since at least the 9th century.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] By the time of the Crusades, every province throughout the Islamic world had mills in operation, from al-Andalus and North Africa to the Middle East and Central Asia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] These mills performed a variety of agricultural and industrial tasks.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Abbasid engineers also developed machines (such as pumps) incorporating crankshafts, employed gears in mills and water-raising machines, and used dams to provide additional power to watermills and water-raising machines.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Such advances made it possible for many industrial tasks that were previously driven by manual labour in ancient times to be mechanized and driven by machinery instead in the medieval Islamic world.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] It has been argued that the industrial use of waterpower had spread from Islamic to Christian Spain, where fulling mills, paper mills, and forge mills were recorded for the first time in Catalonia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] A number of industries were generated during the Arab Agricultural Revolution, including early industries for textiles, sugar, rope-making, matting, silk, and paper.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Latin translations of the 12th century passed on knowledge of chemistry and instrument making in particular.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The agricultural and handicraft industries also experienced high levels of growth during this period.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] While the Abbasids originally gained power by exploiting the social inequalities against non-Arabs in the Umayyad Empire, during Abbasid rule the empire rapidly Arabized, particularly in the Fertile Crescent region (namely Mesopotamia and the Levant) as had begun under Umayyad rule.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] As knowledge was shared in the Arabic language throughout the empire, many people from different nationalities and religions began to speak Arabic in their everyday lives.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Resources from other languages began to be translated into Arabic, and a unique Islamic identity began to form that fused previous cultures with Arab culture, creating a level of civilization and knowledge that was considered a marvel in Europe at the time.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] In contrast to the earlier era, women in Abbasid society were absent from all arenas of the community's central affairs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] While their Muslim forebears led men into battle, started rebellions, and played an active role in community life, as demonstrated in the Hadith literature, Abbasid women were ideally kept in seclusion.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Conquests had brought enormous wealth and large numbers of slaves to the Muslim elite.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The majority of the slaves were women and children, many of whom had been dependents or harem-members of the defeated Sassanian upper classes.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] In the wake of the conquests an elite man could potentially own a thousand slaves, and ordinary soldiers could have ten people serving them.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Even so, slave courtesans (qiyans and jawaris) and princesses produced prestigious and important poetry.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Enough survives to give us access to women's historical experiences, and reveals some vivacious and powerful figures, such as the Sufi mystic Raabi'a al-Adwiyya (714–801 CE), the princess and poet 'Ulayya bint al-Mahdi (777–825 CE), and the singing-girls Shāriyah (c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Each wife in the Abbasid harem had an additional home or flat, with her own enslaved staff of eunuchs and maidservants.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] When a concubine gave birth to a son, she was elevated in rank to umm walad and also received apartments and (slave) servants as a gift.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The status and treatment of Jews, Christians, and non-Muslims in the Abbasid Caliphate was a complex and continually changing issue.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Dhimmis faced some level of discrimination in Abbasid society: they did not have all the privileges of Muslims and had to pay jizya, a tax on non-Muslims.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] However, as people of the book (non-Muslim monotheists), Jews and Christians were allowed to practice their religion and were not required to convert.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Ecclesiastical authorities discouraged practices such as polygamy and sought to regulate interreligious unions, yet ordinary Christians in Iraq and neighboring regions nonetheless participated in both Christian and Islamic marital practices and households across confessional lines.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Christian men might take multiple wives or marry non-Christians, and interreligious marriages, especially those involving Muslim husbands and Christian women, were a persistent concern for Christian jurists, who viewed them as threatening communal boundaries.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] One of the common aspects of the treatment of the dhimmis is that their treatment depended on who the caliph was at the time.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Some Abbasid rulers, like Al-Mutawakkil (822–861 CE) imposed strict restrictions on what dhimmis could wear in public, often yellow garments that distinguished them from Muslims.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Other restrictions al-Mutawakkil imposed included limiting the role of the dhimmis in government, seizing dhimmi housing and making it harder for dhimmis to become educated.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Most other Abbasid caliphs were not as strict as al-Mutawakkil.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] During the reign of Al-Mansur (754–775 CE), it was common for Jews and Christians to influence the overall culture in the caliphate, specifically in Baghdad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Jews and Christians did this by participating in scholarly work.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] It was common that laws that were imposed against dhimmis during one caliph's rule were either discarded or not practiced during future caliphs' reigns.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Al-Mansur and al-Mutawakkil both instituted laws that forbade non-Muslims from participating in public office.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Al-Mansur did not follow his own law very closely, bringing dhimmis back to the caliphate's treasury due to the needed expertise of dhimmis in the area of finance.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Al-Mutawakkil followed the law banning dhimmis from public office more seriously, although, soon after his reign, many of the laws concerning dhimmis participating in government were completely unobserved or at least less strictly observed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] 908–932 CE), who held a similar stance as al-Mutawakkil on barring non-Muslims from public office, himself had multiple Christian secretaries, indicating that non-Muslims still had access to many of the most important figures within the caliphate.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Past having a casual association or just being a secretary to high-ranking Islamic officials, some of them achieved the second highest office after the caliph: the vizier.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Jews and Christians may have had a lower overall status compared to Muslims in the Abbasid Caliphate, but dhimmis were often allowed to hold respectable and even prestigious occupations in some cases, such as doctors and public officeholders.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Jews and Christians were also allowed to be rich even if they were taxed for being a dhimmi.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Dhimmis were capable of moving up and down the social ladder, though this largely depended on the particular caliph.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] An indication as to the social standing of Jews and Christians at the time was their ability to live next to Muslim people.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] While al-Mansur was ruling the caliphate, for instance, it was not uncommon for dhimmis to live in the same neighborhoods as Muslims.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] One of the biggest reasons why dhimmis were allowed to hold prestigious jobs and positions in government is that they were generally important to the well-being of the state and were proficient to excellent with the work at hand.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] In general, Muslims, Jews, and Christians had close relations that could be considered positive at times, especially for Jews, in contrast to how Jews were being treated in Europe.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Many of the laws and restrictions that were imposed on dhimmis often resembled other laws that previous states had used to discriminate against a minority religion, specifically Jewish people.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Romans in the fourth century banned Jewish people from holding public offices, banned Roman citizens from converting to Judaism, and often demoted Jews who were serving in the Roman military.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] In direct contrast, there was an event in which two viziers, Ibn al-Furat and Ali ibn Isa ibn al-Jarrah, argued about Ibn al-Furat's decision to make a Christian the head of the military.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] A previous vizier, Abu Muhammad al-Hasan al-Bazuri, had done so.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] These laws predated al-Mansur's laws against dhimmis and often had similar restrictions, although Roman emperors were often much more strict on enforcing these laws than many Abbasid caliphs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Most of Baghdad's Jews were incorporated into the Arab community and considered Arabic their native language.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Some Jews studied Hebrew in their schools and Jewish religious education flourished.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The united Muslim empire allowed Jews to reconstruct links between their dispersed communities throughout the Middle East.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The city's Talmudic institute helped spread the rabbinical tradition to Europe, and the Jewish community in Baghdad went on to establish ten rabbinical schools and twenty-three synagogues.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Baghdad not only contained the tombs of Muslim saints and martyrs, but also the tomb of Yusha, whose corpse had been brought to Iraq during the first migration of the Jews out of the Levant.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] There were large feasts on certain days, as the Muslims of the empire celebrated Christian holidays as well as their own.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] There were two main Islamic feasts: one marked by the end of Ramadan; the other, "the Feast of Sacrifice".
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The former was especially joyful because children would purchase decorations and sweetmeats; people prepared the best food and bought new clothes.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] At midmorning, the caliph, wearing Muhammad's thobe, would guide officials, accompanied by armed soldiers to the Great Mosque, where he led prayers.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] After the prayer, all those in attendance would exchange the best wishes and hug their kin and companions.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] During those limited number of nights, the palaces were lit up and boats on the Tigris hung lights.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] It was said that Baghdad "glittered 'like a bride'".
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] During the Feast of Sacrifice, sheep were butchered in public arenas and the caliph participated in a large-scale sacrifice in the palace courtyard.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Afterward, the meat would be divided and given to the poor.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] In addition to these two holidays, Shias celebrated the birthdays of Fatimah and Ali ibn Abi Talib.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Matrimonies and births in the royal family were observed by all in the empire.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The announcement that one of the caliph's sons could recite the Koran smoothly was greeted by communal jubilation.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] When Harun developed this holy talent, the people lit torches and decorated the streets with wreaths of flowers, and his father, Al-Mahdi, freed 500 slaves.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Of all the holidays imported from other cultures and religions, the one most celebrated in Baghdad (a city with many Persians) was Nowruz, which celebrated the arrival of spring.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] In a ceremonial ablution introduced by Persian troops, residents sprinkled themselves with water and ate almond cakes.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The palaces of the imperial family were lit up for six days and nights.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The Abbasids also celebrated the Persian holiday of Mihraj, which marked the onset of winter (signified with pounding drums), and Sadar, when homes burned incense and the masses would congregate along the Tigris to witness princes and viziers pass by.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The Abbasid army amassed an array of siege equipment, such as catapults, mangonels, battering rams, ladders, grappling irons, and hooks.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] All such weaponry was operated by military engineers.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] However, the primary siege weapon was the *manjaniq*, a type of siege weapon that was comparable to the trebuchet employed in Western medieval times.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] From the seventh century onward, it had largely replaced torsion artillery.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] By Harun al-Rashid's time, the Abbasid army employed fire grenades.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The Abbasids also utilized field hospitals and ambulances drawn by camels.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The cavalry was entirely covered in iron, with helmets.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Similar to medieval knights, their only exposed spots were the end of their noses and small openings in front of their eyes.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Their foot soldiers were issued spears, swords, and pikes, and (in line with Persian fashion) trained to stand so solidly that, one contemporary wrote "you would have thought them held fast by clamps of bronze".
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Although the Abbasids never retained a substantial regular army, the caliph could recruit a considerable number of soldiers in a short time when needed from levies.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] There were also cohorts of regular troops who received steady pay and a special forces unit.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] At any moment, 125,000 Muslim soldiers could be assembled along the Byzantine frontier, Baghdad, Medina, Damascus, Rayy, and other geostrategic locations in order to quell any unrest.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] During the Abbasid revolution, Abu Muslim's Khorasani army, composed largely of Arab settlers disillusioned with Umayyad rule, marched under black banners, forming a powerful force that swept westward in open revolt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] In Baghdad there were many Abbasid military leaders who were or said they were of Arab descent.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] However, it is clear that most of the ranks were of Iranian origin, the vast majority being from Khurasan and Transoxiana, not from western Iran or Azerbaijan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Most of the Khurasani soldiers who brought the Abbasids to power were Arabs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The standing army of the Muslims in Khurasan was overwhelmingly Arab.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The unit organization of the Abbasids was designed with the goal of ethnic and racial equality among supporters.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] When Abu Muslim recruited officers along the Silk Road, he registered them based not on their tribal or ethno-national affiliations but on their current places of residence.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Under the Abbasids, Iranian peoples became better represented in the army and bureaucracy as compared to before.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] He abolished the old *jund* system created by Umar and diverted the salaries of the original Arab military descendants to the Turkic slave soldiers.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The Turkic soldiers transformed the style of warfare, as they were known as capable horse archers, trained from childhood to ride.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] This military was now drafted from the ethnic groups of the faraway borderlands, and were completely separate from the rest of society.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] This led to the decline of the caliphate starting with the Anarchy at Samarra.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] As a result of such a vast Empire, the caliphate was decentralized and divided into 24 provinces.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Harun's vizier enjoyed close to unchecked powers.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Under Harun, a special "bureau of confiscation" was created.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] This governmental wing made it possible for the vizier to seize the property and riches of any corrupt governor or civil servant.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] In addition, it allowed governors to confiscate the estates of lower-ranking officials.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Finally, the caliph could impose the same penalty on a vizier who fell from grace.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] As one later caliph put it: "The vizier is our representative throughout the land and amongst our subjects.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Every regional metropolis had a post office and hundreds of roads were paved in order to link the imperial capital with other cities and towns.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The empire employed a system of relays to deliver mail.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The central post office in Baghdad even had a map with directions that noted the distances between each town.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The roads were provided with roadside inns, hospices, and wells and could reach eastward through Persia and Central Asia, to as far as China.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The post office not only enhanced civil services but also served as intelligence for the caliph.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Mailmen were employed as spies who kept an eye on local affairs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Early in the days of the caliphate, the Barmakids took the responsibility of shaping the civil service.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The family had roots in a Buddhist monastery in northern Afghanistan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] In the early 8th century, the family converted to Islam and began to take on a sizable part of the civil administration for the Abbasids.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Capital poured into the caliphate's treasury from a variety of taxes, including a real estate tax; a levy on cattle, gold and silver, and commercial wares; a special tax on non-Muslims; and customs dues.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Under Harun al-Rashid, maritime trade through the Persian Gulf thrived, with Arab vessels trading as far south as Madagascar and as far east as China, Korea, and Japan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The growing economy of Baghdad and other cities inevitably led to the demand for luxury items and formed a class of entrepreneurs who organized long-range caravans for the trade and then the distribution of their goods.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] A whole section in the East Baghdad suq was dedicated to Chinese goods.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Much of this direct maritime trade was oriented toward Iraqi markets, particularly Basra and Baghdad, which functioned as major destinations for goods arriving from Tang China.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] From the seventh to the tenth centuries, merchants from the Gulf served Iraqi markets through direct sea routes linking the Persian Gulf to the South China coast, especially Guangzhou, as attested by both contemporary textual sources and archaeological evidence.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The ninth-century Belitung shipwreck, carrying a large cargo of Chinese ceramics, illustrates the scale of this trade and its connection to demand in Iraq and the wider Abbasid realm.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Arabs traded with the Baltic region and made it as far north as the British Isles.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Tens of thousands of Arab coins have been discovered in parts of Russia and Sweden, which bear witness to the comprehensive trade networks set up by the Abbasids.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] King Offa of Mercia (in England) minted gold coins similar to those of the Abbasids in the eighth century.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Muslim merchants employed ports in Bandar Siraf, Basra, and Aden and some Red Sea ports to travel and trade with India and South East Asia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Land routes were also utilized through Central Asia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Arab businessmen were present in China as early as the eighth century.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Arab merchants sailed the Caspian Sea to reach and trade with Bukhara and Samarkand.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] During the ninth and tenth centuries, large quantities of opaque glazed pottery were produced in southern Iraq, within the heartlands of the Abbasid Caliphate, and exported as a mass-produced commercial commodity.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Finds of this Iraqi ware at sites across the Middle East, South Africa, and Southeast Asia demonstrate sustained commercial interaction between Iraq and the wider Indian Ocean world.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Most of the exported vessels were standardized and practical in design, indicating that they were produced for large-scale commercial trade rather than for elite or luxury use.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Many caravans and goods never made it to their intended destinations.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Some Chinese exports perished in fires, while other ships sank.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] It was said that anybody who made it to China and back unharmed was blessed by God.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Common sea routes were also plagued by pirates who built and crewed vessels that were faster than most merchant ships.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] It is said that many of the adventures at sea in the Sinbad tales were based on historical fiction of mariners of the day.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The Abbasids also established overland trade with Africa, largely for gold and slaves.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] When trade with Europe ceased due to hostilities, Jews served as a link between the two hostile worlds.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] The Abbasids engaged in extensive trade with the Italian maritime republics of Venice and Genoa, from the 11th century.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Venetian merchants facilitated the exchange of high-value goods such as spices, silk, and precious metals from the East.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] In return, Venice exported European manufactured goods and luxury items.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] While Genoese merchants traded in luxury goods like spices, textiles, and other high-demand items.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] Genoa's strategic position in the Mediterranean enabled it to integrate into the broader Mediterranean trade network, connecting the Abbasid Caliphate with other European markets.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] These trade relations played a key role in linking the medieval Mediterranean with the broader Islamic world.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abbasid-p02] This exchange of goods, alongside cultural and technological transfers, fostered a more interconnected medieval global economy.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The *Abora I* originated as a school project in Germany using locally grown Giant (Miscanthus).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] All subsequent vessels were commissioned to boat builders from the Aymara nation living at Lake Titicaca in Bolivia; the same boat builders worked already for Thor Heyerdahl.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] As building material they used the very sturdy and durable Totora reed which is far better suited for this purpose.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The Abora (or Abora I, in retrospective) was designed, built and used between 1996 and 1999.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] It sailed from Alghero (Sardinia, Italy) to Piombino (Tuscany, Italy).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The Abora II sailed in 2002 across the Mediterranean: from Alexandria (Egypt) to Beirut (Lebanon), Cyprus and back to Alexandria.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] It thus became the first modern-time reed boat which managed to complete an extended round trip and then to return to the port of departure.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The departure at Alexandria coincided with the inauguration of the Bibliotheca Alexandrina, the new Alexandrian library; the Abora crew brought some gifts (books) from Thor Heyerdahl's Kon-Tiki Museum in Oslo, Norway in honor of the inauguration.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Thor Heyerdahl had also personally supported the preparation of the Abora I and II expeditions; by coincidence the launch of the Abora II took place on 18 April 2002, which turned out to be the day when Thor Heyerdahl died.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] With Abora III, Dominique Görlitz attempted the first ever crossing of the Atlantic from West to East with a reed boat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Görlitz considered it possible that such events actually took place in antiquity.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] As a motivation, he particularly quoted the finding of traces of cocaine and nicotine in Egyptian mummies, including chopped tobacco leaves and the remains of a Mexican tobacco beetle in the mummy of Ramses II (1298–1213 BC).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Mainstream scholars have shown that there are possible Old World sources of cocaine and nicotine.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The finding of tobacco leaves became a popular topic in fringe literature and the media and it was seen as proof of contact between Ancient Egypt and the New World.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Compared to an East-West crossing, which Thor Heyerdahl successfully demonstrated in 1970 with the barely maneuverable reed boat Ra II, a west-east crossing of the Atlantic is much more difficult.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] This must be done further north along the Gulf Stream.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] However, the Gulf Stream does not flow evenly, but forms huge eddies.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Furthermore, the winds there blow inconsistently from all directions.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] This means that this crossing cannot take place as a practically pure drift, as in the case of the Ra II in the opposite direction, rather the reed boat must be able to cover longer distances by wind even under adverse conditions.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The hull of the boat was again manufactured in Bolivia (in 2006).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The boat was finalized one year later in New York.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The *Abora III* expedition started in New York on July 11, 2007.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] An initially supportive Azores high dissolved completely in early August, and the crew faced one storm after another.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Two of these storm lows reached hurricane strengths with wind speeds of up to 51 knots.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] These bad weather fronts affected the Abora III, but did not yet lead to serious damage.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] However, three side swords broke during the first storm, but this happened close enough to the American mainland that replacement swords could be delivered and replaced.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] In mid-August, after 500 km of a total of around 6000 km, a calm delayed the trip.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] A three-day hurricane then damaged the rear of the Abora III on August 27, 2007 in such a way that it had to be separated from the hull. during the subsequent 4 days, the crew reinstalled the intact rudder and moved the mast further towards the bow.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The modified Abora III could temporarily set full sail and even sail up to 90° to the wind.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] On September 4, the next storm with wind force 10 severely affected both the Abora III and an escort vessel approaching from the Azores.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Therefore, the crew abandoned the experiment on September 5, 2007, about 900 kilometres from the Azores, the 11-member crew and switched to the escort vessel.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The reed boat was left to the sea after cutting the strings that held the hull together.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] A message in a bottle thrown into the water before the boat was evacuated was found in the Bahamas in October 2010.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] This illustrates that a West-East crossing of the Atlantic requires an intact sailing ability of the boat (in contrast to the opposite direction: Thor Heyerdahl's Ra II was also badly damaged in 1970, but was still able to drift to America with the help of the Canary Current).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The aim of the Abora IV expedition was to retrace possible trade contacts between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Herodotus mentioned in his *Histories* trading contacts between the Egyptians and the Caucasus on the eastern Black Sea coast; according to him, especially metals were imported into Egypt via this route.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] According to the expedition leader Dominique Görlitz's assumption, tin and amber were also exported from Central Europe to Egypt via the Balkans and finally the Black Sea to the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Varna in Bulgaria was chosen as the starting point of the expedition both because of the place's historic significance (Varna Necropolis) and for practical reasons; the expedition received strong support from the Varna Archaeological Museum.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The final construction took place from May to August 2019 in Beloslav near Varna.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Due to the late delivery of the prefabricated reed bundles from Bolivia and due to extremely bad weather conditions in Bulgaria, the launch of the Abora was greatly delayed and the start of the expedition could only take place on August 16.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The Abora IV sailed through the Black Sea to Istanbul in Turkey, then through the Bosporus (on tow, for safety reasons), through the Marmara Sea and into the Dardanelles (again on tow) to Çanakkale (a modern harbor near ancient Troy), then onward into the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Here, the first station was the Greek island of Limnos, where the vessel managed to enter and to leave the prehistoric port of Poliochni without being supported by a tug boat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] From there, it sailed on to Santorini, hereby managing to pass several straits between several Greek islands.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] During the expedition, Dominique Görlitz received the offer from the Turkish Ministry of Culture in Ankara to exhibit the reed boat in the Patara Archeology Park (near Antalya) as a permanent exhibit.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Thereupon it was decided to sail from Santorini straight to Kaş (a modern harbour near Patara) at the Lycian coast.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Here, the Abora IV arrived on 19 September; the entire distance from Varna to Kaş was covered in 34 days.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] As planned, the vessel is now on permanent display on the agora of the ancient city of Patara.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Like most experimental-archaeological projects, also the ABORA projects could only examine the technical feasibility of a proposed method.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Whether these methods were indeed exploited in the past, can only be clarified by archaeological finds.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The Abora expeditions specifically acclaimed to have reproduced an ancient navigation technology based on the use of leeboards.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] The expedition leader Dominique Görlitz presented various examples of such depictions (with and without leeboards) in his books and on the official project website.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Ethnological evidence for the use of large navigable rafts exists only from South America, where such rafts were in use also after the Spanish conquest.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] These rafts used so-called centerboards or guaras; they could be navigated even without a rudder.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Also Thor Heyerdahl conducted already some experiments using those guaras.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Therefore, Heyerdahl followed the ABORA expeditions with great interest until his death in 2002.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Positive appraisals of the ABORA projects came also from various other scientists, for instance Havva Iskan (Akdeniz University, Turkey, lead archaeologist at Patara, where the ABORA IV is now on permanent display).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] In 2007, during the ABORA III expedition, a critical article appeared in the German popular-scientific journal *Spektrum der Wissenschaft*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] It quotes a German Egyptologist who doubts Görlitz' interpretation of details of boat depictions as leeboards, as well as his assumptions with regard to the age of those depictions, but does not offer an alternative explanation.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abora-expeditions] Specifically with regard to the Abora III expedition (attempt of a West-East Atlantic crossing), doubts are also expressed about alleged evidences for tobacco or cocaine use in ancient Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The twin temples were originally carved out of the mountainside in the 13th century BC, during the 19th Dynasty reign of the Pharaoh Ramesses II.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Their huge external rock relief figures of Ramesses II have become iconic.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] His wife, Nefertari, and children can be seen in smaller figures by his feet.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Sculptures inside the Great Temple commemorate Ramesses II's heroic leadership at the Battle of Kadesh.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The complex was relocated in its entirety in 1968 to higher ground to avoid it being submerged by Lake Nasser, the Aswan Dam reservoir.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] As part of the International Campaign to Save the Monuments of Nubia, an artificial hill was made from a domed structure to house the Abu Simbel Temples, under the supervision of a Polish archaeologist, Kazimierz Michałowski, from the Polish Centre of Mediterranean Archaeology University of Warsaw.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The Abu Simbel complex, and other relocated temples from Nubian sites such as Philae, Amada, Wadi es-Sebua, are part of the UNESCO World Heritage Site known as the Nubian Monuments.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] During his reign, Ramesses II embarked on an extensive building program throughout Egypt and Nubia, which Egypt controlled.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] As a major source of gold and many other precious trade goods, Nubia was of great importance to the Egyptians.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] He therefore built several grand temples in order to impress upon the Nubians Egypt's might and Egyptianize the people of Nubia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The most prominent temples are the rock-cut temples near the modern village of Abu Simbel, at the Second Nile Cataract, the border between Lower Nubia and Upper Nubia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] There are two temples, the Great Temple, dedicated to Ramesses II himself, and the Small Temple, dedicated to his chief wife Queen Nefertari.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Construction of the temple complex started in c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] 1264 BC and lasted for about 20 years, until 1244 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] It was known as the Temple of Ramesses, Beloved by Amun.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] With the passage of time, the temples fell into disuse and the Great Temple eventually became mostly covered by a sand dune.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] By the 6th century BC, the sand already covered the statues of the main temple up to their knees.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The temple remained unknown to Europeans until March 1813, when the Swiss researcher Johann Ludwig Burckhardt found the small temple and top frieze of the main temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In 1815, British politician and explorer William John Bankes, accompanied only by servants and guides, travelled from Cairo up the Nile as far as the Second Cataract.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] On the way he visited Abu Simbel, but was unable to enter the Great Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] He vowed to return with sufficient resources to investigate the site in detail.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In early 1816, the French ex-consul Bernardino Drovetti made an attempt to excavate Abu Simbel, leaving 300 piastres with the local sheikh to pay for digging out the temple entrance, before continuing upriver to Wadi Halfa.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Upon his return, the sheikh returned the money to him as the local Nubians had been unable to comprehend what value these small pieces of metal had, and so no work had been undertaken in order to receive them.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] A few months later in early September 1816, the Italian explorer Giovanni Belzoni arrived, having heard about the site from Burckhardt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] He recorded that the Great Temple presented just ‘one figure of enormous size, with the head and shoulders only projecting out of the sand.’ He was able to convince the sheikh that coins had value and agreed on a price of two piastres a day per man to work at the site.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Belzoni succeeded in exposing the figure over the doorway to the Great Temple, and the head and shoulders of the north-central colossi of Ramesses II, before having to abandon the effort to clear any more sand due to a lack of food and money to pay the local Nubians.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] After 22 days’ work, he and his party were able to enter the Great Temple on 1 August 1817.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Among the party that accompanied them were the Italian physician and artist Alessandro Ricci; the young French draughtsman Louis Maurice Adolphe Linant de Bellefonds, Jean-Nicolas Huyot, and the naturalist Baron Albert von Sack.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] They stopped from 23 January to 18 February 1819 at Abu Simbel on a journey south that was to take them as far as the Second Cataract.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Of that time, three weeks were consumed in excavating the whole of the southernmost colossus of Ramesses II down to its feet.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] After finding graffiti on its feet Bankes uncovered the legs of the second colossus and was rewarded by finding further graffiti.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Bankes had hoped to permanently remove the sand and dump it in the Nile but this proved to be impossible with the resources they had, so they simply moved the sand back and held it in place by damping it with large amounts of water.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] They then covered what they had previously excavated as they moved from one statue to another documenting what they had found.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] They left the Great Temple partly more exposed than they had found it.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Later, after travelling independently, Hyde revisited Abu Simbel from 26 March 1819 until 2 April 1819.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] By 27 January they had removed enough sand to be able to enter the Great Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] To endure the heat the men stripped almost naked.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Using 20 to 50 small wax candles for illumination, they were soon at work drawing what they found.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Days after Banke's departure, the French architect and archaeologist Franz Christian Gau arrived at Abu Simbel on his return downriver after traveling as far as the Second Cataract.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] He found the entrance to the interior of the Great Temple partially blocked and had to crawl through on his stomach, worried all the time that the sand may fall down again and block it.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] He found the conditions so exhausting and could only manage a few hours inside each day, with insufficient light available to create drawings.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Upon his return to Europe he published his research in 1822 under the title, *Les antiquités de la Nubie. ou monumens inédits des bords du Nil situés entre la première et deuxième cataracte, dessinés et mésurés, en 1819*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Upon his return to France Huyot sent reproductions of the meticulous drawings he had made at Abu Simbel to Jean-François Champollion, who at the time was on a quest to decipher Egyptian hieroglyphs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Upon receiving them on 14 September 1822, the first cartouche Champollion saw he was able to decipher and connect to Ramesses.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] This allowed him to translate a second cartouche as belonging to Thutmose.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] As he said “Thutmose” aloud, Champollion had the epiphany that hieroglyphics was a hybrid system that mixed symbolic and phonetic signs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] This breakthrough allowed Champollion to become the first man in 2,000 years to read hieroglyphs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] From August 1828 to 28 November 1829, Champollion worked with his collaborator and friend Ippolito Rosellini to lead a joint Franco-Tuscan scientific expedition to Egypt to confirm and collect data that would verify that his hieroglyphic system was correct.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Among the expedition's members was Alessandro Ricci who had previously worked with Bankes.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Supplied with a large sailing boat by Muhammad Ali, they reached Abu Simbel on 26 November 1828.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] They spent two weeks at Abu Simbel, first having to clear the doorway into interior of the Great Temple as the sand that had been cleared by Bankes had returned.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] During their time there the expedition copied all of the temple reliefs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Prior to departure they removed the palisade they had installed to hold back the sand, which immediately flowed down to cover the entrance to a depth of 2 metres (6.6 ft) above the cornice.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] A detailed early description of the temples, together with contemporaneous line drawings, can be found in Edward William Lane's *Description of Egypt* (1825–1828).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Two decades after Belzoni's removal of sand to create an entrance to the Great Temple, the Scottish painter David Roberts traveled up the Nile from Cairo and reached Abu Simbel on 9 November 1838.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] He spent time in the area making detailed sketches before returning downstream on 11 November.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Upon his return to London in 1839, Roberts created detailed watercolours from his sketches.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Four watercolours of Abu Simbel were included as lithographs in volumes 4 and 5 of The Holy Land, Syria, Idumea, Arabia, Egypt, and Nubia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In 1842 Robert Stewart, Viscount Castlereagh and his party visited Abu Simbel and were able to enter the Great Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] He reported that the exterior northernmost colossi of Ramesses II bore traces of whitewash, having been applied by someone taking a plaster cast of the face.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The first European woman to visit Abu Simbel was the English writer Isabella Frances Romer in December 1845, who marked the occasion by cutting her name into the throne of the southern colossus.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In 1849, the writer Maxime Du Camp was commissioned by the French Ministry of Public Instruction to record monuments and inscriptions in the Middle East using the newly developed technology of photography.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Accompanied by his friend, the novelist Gustave Flaubert, he spent the years from 1849 to 1851 completing the mission, which Flaubert recorded in journals and letters, later published in English in 1972 as in *Flaubert in Egypt: A Sensibility on Tour*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] After ascending the Nile as far as the second cataract, they stopped on their return downstream at Abu Simbel, arriving at 9 am on 27 March 1850 and departing on 30 March.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] After docking, he had his crew begin removing the sand from around the head of the fourth colossus of the Great Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] He commenced taking photographs the following day, taking three of the facade of the Small Temple on 28 March, and five of the Grand Temple on 29 March, as well as one of the entire complex from the other side of the Nile, and various aspects of the Great Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In a number of photographs, Du Camp had his servant and occasional laboratory assistant Louis Sasseti pose to provide scale.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] At the end of his expedition, Du Camp bought back to France 214 photographs of Cairo, Thebes, Philae, and Abu Simbel, as well as Palestinian and Syrian monuments and landscapes.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Of these, 125 calotypes (including 10 of Abu Simbel) were printed by Blanquart-Evrard and included in a book written by Du Camp upon his return to France called *Egypte, Nubie, Palestine et Syrie: Dessins photographiques recueillis pendant les annees 1849, 1850, 1851*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Published by Gide and Baudry in 1852, it was the first French printed book to be illustrated with photographs and was a great success.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Du Camp was followed by French civil engineer Félix Teynard (1817–1892), who photographed sites along the Nile River in 1851 and 1852.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The resulting photographs were published in thirty-two installments of five plates, beginning in 1853 as *Égypte et Nubie: sites et monuments les plus intéressants pour l'étude de l'art et de l'histoire*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] A complete edition was published in London in 1858.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] American John Beasley Greene, a Paris-based archaeologist, photographed Abu Simbel in 1854.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The best known of the early photographers of Egypt was Englishman Francis Frith, who made three journeys to Egypt, Syria and the Holy Land between 1856 and 1860, first photographing Abu Simbel in 1857.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Other 19th century photographers of Abu Simbel included Pascal Sébah and Antonio Beato.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In the winter of 1873–1874 Amelia Edwards, accompanied by her friend Lucy Renshaw and their lady's maid Jenny Lane, were among a party of 25 who journeyed southwards down the Nile from Cairo in a hired dahabiyeh (manned houseboat).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Edwards later published her account of the journey in the bestselling *A Thousand Miles up the Nile* (1877).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Lane also left behind a journal describing their adventures.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] While in Cairo, Edwards had made the acquaintance of diarist Marianne Brocklehurst and her companion Mary Booth who ended up accompanying them on another dahabiyeh.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Brocklehurst's own travel diary of the voyage was published in 2005.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Throughout their respective travels Brocklehurst and Edwards competed with each other in the illegal removal of Egyptian antiquities.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Edwards' party ultimately reached Abu Simbel in moonlight on the evening of 31 January 1874, departing down river on 18 February after a four-day excursion to Wadi Halfa.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] On 16 February, a member of Edward's party, the painter Andrew McCallum discovered what was originally called the South Chapel, but which is now known as the Chapel of Thoth.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The crew were soon all at work removing sand away from the entrance which by 2pm allowed the party to crawl in on their hands and knees and by 4pm to enter with ease.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In 1874, Thomas Cook instituted a steamer service that operated between Aswan and Wadi Halfa, passing Abu Simbel.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The 1892 Baedeker travel guide reported that "Cook's tourist-steamers usually reach Abu-Simbel in the evening of the third day, in time to permit of a visit to the temples before night.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Next morning they proceed to Wadi Halfah.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In December 1892, the Egyptian Department of Public Works identified that there were insecure amounts of rock overhanging the façade of the Great Temple which, if they fell, would badly damage the colossi below.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] At the insistence of civil engineer Sir William Willcocks, a request was made to Army Headquarters for the Royal Engineers to undertake an operation to preserve the Great Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In response, a 12-men detachment of the 24th (Fortress) Company under the command of Lieutenant James Henry L'Estrange Johnstone, arrived at Abu Simbel by the gunboat *El Teb* on 6 February 1893.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Arrangements were made for the engineers to be billeted on site in one of Thomas Cook's Post Boats.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Upon arrival, they found that a large fragment of rock above the left-hand colossus was close to toppling over onto it, while an even larger piece of overhanging rock near another colossus was cracked all around.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Many more tons of loose rock also required attention.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Great care had to be undertaken, as much of the Great Temple was still partly buried under drift sand and the slope was extremely steep.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Local Nubians were hired to create a path up a sand slope north of the temple's façade and along the hillside above.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] On 10 February, a large loose rock poised on the cornice immediately above the temple entrance was removed by means of tackle attached to a holdfast.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Two days later, work began on securing a 70 long tons (71 t) rock with screw jacks and a four-inch steel wire rope, attached via a holdfast of steel bars inserted into the level rock above.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Once secure, the massive rock took a week to be broken up and removed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] On 27 February, while cleaning sand and stones from the rock face above the cornice, the engineers found a massive crack that severed an overhanging mass weighing approximately 650 long tons (660 t) from the solid cliff.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] They made excellent progress breaking it up by mechanical means until they encountered a very hard layer, which would need explosives to shatter.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] However, as they had been forbidden from transporting explosives on the railway and steamboats, the engineers sourced it from 9-pounder ammunition on the *El Teb* instead.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] As each piece was broken off, they were hauled up the slope by a winch and tackle, until all that remained was a block of approximately 100 long tons (100 t) weight, lying well back from the edge of a flat ledge.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] With the cliff face now secure, the removed rock was used to construct two walls at the head of the depression between the two temples to prevent buildup of more drift sand from burying the Great Temple again, and to construct a hard stone slope.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The engineers began on 5 April to remove the sand from the entrance to the temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The engineers also repaired a number of the remaining baboon statues on the cornice with cement and furnished one with a new leg.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The removal of the sand exposed an unsuspected grave at the southern end of the cutting in the rock, near the Chapel of Thoth.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] It contained Major Benjamin Tidswell of the Royal Dragoons, who had died of dysentery on 18 June 1885 at Abu Simbel while serving with the Nile Expedition's Heavy Camel Regiment.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The burial party had heaped sand on top of his grave to protect it from the elements and animals.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The engineers also cleared away debris which had piled up in front of the entrance to the Chapel of Thoth.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The project was completed and inspected by the Public Works Department on 9 April 1893.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In all, nearly 850 long tons (860 t) of dangerous material had been removed, with no accidents while working in a temperature of 107 °F (42 °C) in the shade, at a cost that was less than one-half the original estimate of £1,000.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] They also suspected that it might be concealing other structures.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Therefore, between 1909 and 1910 under the leadership of Alessandro Barsanti, the sand was permanently cleared away.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The sand was disposed of down the slope in front of the temples so as to form a wide platform, which was held in place by a retaining wall along the riverbank.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The opportunity was also taken to install a flight of steps from the new platform down to the river.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] When the drift was removed, a row of statues was discovered along the terrace in front of the colossi.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] These consisted of figures of the Pharaoh and of the sacred hawk of the sun alternating along the entire length.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] A previously unknown small building, now known as the Chapel of Re-Harakhty, was also found.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] An examination of the colossi found that that they were in a very dangerous condition, which was stabilized by inserting cement into the cracks and cavities.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Iron pins were used to hold together the smaller cracks.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In addition, a numerous repairs were made in the inner halls of the Great Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Since its discovery in 1893, Gaston Maspero, the head of the Egyptian Department of Antiquities, had arranged for the grave of Benjamin Tidswell to be maintained once a year.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In 1908, it was noticed that the preceding Nile inundation had undermined the grave, and that the next flood would wash it away entirely.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Therefore, in 1909 the remains were removed and laid in a lead coffin, which was placed in a wooden coffin and temporary stored in a chamber within the Great Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] On 3 January 1910, the remains were permanently interred in the corridor to the south of the façade, between the base of the southernmost colossus and the rock face, with a granite tombstone installed over it.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In the early 1950s, the only public transportation to Abu Simbel was a twice-weekly boat that carried passengers and cargo between Aswan and the Sudan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In 1959, an international donations campaign to save the monuments of Nubia began: the southernmost relics of this ancient civilization were under threat from the rising waters of the Nile that were about to result from the construction of the Aswan High Dam.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The resulting lake would raise the water level at Abu Simbel by up to 60 metres (200 ft).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Once submerged the water would cause the sandstone from which they were constructed to lose its strength and durability.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] A number of schemes were proposed in early 1962 from various institutions and individuals on how to save the temples.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] One scheme to save the temples, based on an idea by Irish film producer William MacQuitty, was to leave them where they were and building a dam around them, containing crystal-clear filtered water kept at the same height as the muddy Nile water outside.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Visitors would then have looked at the engulfed temples from curved observation galleries on three levels.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] He envisaged that in time the dam would be outdated by atomic power and the water level lowered, restoring the temples to their original state.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] As they considered that raising the temples ignored the effect of erosion of the sandstone by desert winds, the idea was taken up and turned into a proposal by architects Maxwell Fry and Jane Drew, working with civil engineer Ove Arup.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Unfortunately, the proposal proved unfeasible: as sandstone is porous, the water would eventually cause the temples to crumble.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Another scheme proposed by an American construction executive was to construct concrete barges under the temples and then allow the rising lake water to raise them.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Eventually two proposals were identified as being technically feasible.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] One from André Coyne and Jean Bellier, from the French engineering firm of Coyne et Bellier (now Tractebel Engineering) was for the temples to remain in position, protected by a curved 240 feet (73 m) high thin-walled concrete dam with a reflecting pool in front of the temples.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Visitors would arrive by boat and disembark at the top of the dam.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Pumps would be required to permanently manage the seepage of water from the lake through the dam.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] This idea was dismissed due to the risks of the extensive drainage system failing but also due to its estimated cost of $82 million, high ongoing operating costs, and the belief that the temples would slowly be damaged by damp arising from capillary attraction.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The second was from the Italian firm of Italconsult, following an idea by Pierre Gassola.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] They proposed cutting away the top of the cliff above the temples, before cutting behind them to sever them from the cliff.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] A reinforced concrete platform would then be inserted under them and after enclosing each in a massive concrete box they would then be raised on hydraulic jacks up 200 feet (61 m) to a higher location.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The Great Temple was estimated to weigh 250,000 tons while the combined estimated weight of the Small Temple and its concrete box was 100,000 tons.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] No structure of this weight had ever been lifted before, and as well as its significant cost it would take three years before it would be possible to actually commence raising the temples, despite the reservoir was expected to begin being raised in the autumn of 1964.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] This proposal was estimated to cost $62 million.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Despite this UNESCO announced on 10 June 1962 that it was their preferred option and commissioned the Swedish engineering consulting firm Vattenbyggnadsbyrån (VBB) to oversee the project.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] While attempts were being made to raise the funds need to undertaken the project the Egyptian Minister of Culture Tharwat Okasha had secretly commissioned VBB to investigate a possible backup to the French and Italian proposals.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] After solving various problems VBB proposed disassembling the temples into blocks as large as possible and lifting them up to a higher location and reassembling them.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] There were concerns however that as sandstone is made of grains of quartz that are weakly connected any cutting and lifting would lead to cracking and breaking of blocks with the possibly of up to a third being ruined.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] By early June 1963 Egypt had adopted the VBB proposal as not only had it a realistic chance of being able to save the temples before they were flooded but was estimated to cost US$36 million, half the cost of the other proposals.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] By 14 June 1963 agreement had been also been reached on how to finance the work.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Egypt would contribute $11.5 million, 43 UNESCO member states another $7.7 million with the United States in addition intending to fund up to a third of estimated cost.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] It was hoped that private contributions would make up the remaining amount.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Prior to committing to its contribution the United States had canvased 11 engineers, archaeologists and Egyptologists, who all supported VBB's proposal.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Two weeks later the government of Egypt invited bids from firms wishing to work on the project to be submitted by 15 September 1963.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] At the time it was expected that approximately 40 companies would submit bids.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The publicity about the potential loss of the temples had by this time increased the number of visitors over the previous three years from approximately 50 a year to as many as 150 a day.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Having already successfully relocated the Temple of Kalabsha, the German construction company Hochtief was appointed to lead the team of contractors, which was called “Joint Venture Abu Simbel” (JVAS).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Walter Jurecha was appointed project manager, with Carl Theodar Mackel in charge of site activities.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Joining Hochtief in the joint venture were the Egyptian firm Atlas, the French construction company Grands Travaux de Marseille, the Italian civil construction company Impressit-Girola-Lodigiani (Impregilo) and from Sweden Skånska cementgjuteriet (Skanska) and Svenska Entreprenad AB (Sentab).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The evolvement of Swedish companies in JVAS led to orders being given to Atlas Copco (to supply pneumatic powered drilling equipment) and Sandvik AB (to develop and manufacture the required saws).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] VBB led by Karl Fredrick Ward (as the project's head engineer) was retained as the project's consulting engineers and architects.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Their involvement was to last for approximately 10 years.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The actual cutting and a reassembly of the temples was entrusted to the Impreglio, who intended to employ *marmisti* (stone cutters) who had learnt their trade cutting marble in the Carrara quarries to undertake the actual cutting.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Two international committees containing archaeologists, architects and engineers provided technical advice to the joint venture, while the Egyptian government interests was represented on site by their own resident engineer who was supported by archaeologists from the Department of Antiquities.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] By the spring of 1964 approximately 1,000 people were being employed by the project at Abu Simbel.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] For the first year of the project they lived in houseboats, tents and huts until by 1965 a proper construction village could be established, complete with a mosque, cafeteria, cinema, sports facilities and a swimming pool.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] As there was no school, children were taught by correspondence.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Supplies and equipment from Cairo took four to six weeks to reach the site, while it took five months from Europe.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Based on the proposed construction schedule for the Aswan Dam it was necessary for the temples to be removed from their existing location by 15 August 1966 if they were not to be inundated by the raising lake level.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] As it was expected that by the winter of 1964 that the lake level would be 16 feet (4.9 m) higher than the base of the Small Temple and 4 feet (1.2 m) higher than the base of the Great Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] As a result, the first task was in November 1963 to commence constructing an 82 feet (25 m) high temporary cofferdam formed around steel sheets that were filled with earth from both sides.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] This material was sourced from the excavations above behind the temples.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Work continued in three 12-hour shifts, 24 hours a day, seven days a week until the 370 metres (1,210 ft) long dam was finished and it then had to be increased in height to 27 metres (89 ft) when higher floodwaters in 1964 than expected threatened to overtop it.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Water seeping through the dam forced the installation of three drainage tunnels connected to a pumping station which used 25 pumps to remove 750,000 US gal (2,800,000 L) of water an hour. it was then found that water was seeping up via the soil under the cofferdam.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] To prevent it reaching the temples, drilling rigs were bought in to drill 15 deep wells in each of which an underwater pump was installed to remove any seepage.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The sand reached as high as the bottom of the uppermost frieze, which was itself protected by the construction of a temporary structure overtop of it.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Steel tunnels were installed through the sand to allow workers to access the interior chambers of the temples.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Inside they installed scaffolding to support the ceilings and walls, during removal of the cliff above them.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Initially excavators were used to remove the cliff from the uppermost 190 feet (58 m) of the cliff, but due to the increasing risk of damage from vibrations, pneumatic hammers were used to remove the remaining 60,000 short tons (54,000 t) to within 2.5 feet (0.76 m) of the ceiling and walls.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In total approximately 300,000 tons of rock were removed to free the temples from the cliff.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] To assist in assessing where to make the required cuts the project team had the use of detailed drawings of the facades of the two temples which had prepared in 1959 by French National Geographic Institute.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The cuts were intended to be only 0.25 inches (6.4 mm) wide which will assist in ensuring that they would be as close to invisible as possible once the temples were reassembled.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] After numerous tests to determine the best means of holding the delicate sandstone of the blocks together, Egyptian workers spent seven months injecting the surface indentations and cracks of the interiors and facades with an epoxy resin.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Tests had already been conducted with various types of powered and manual saws to determine the best way of cutting the stone.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] With a few exceptions it was determined that only handsaws would be employed on the facades and interiors.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The most common types used were Novello saws (which had diamond-tipped teeth) and helicoidal saws.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Once the sandstone had been strengthened with epoxy, work commenced on reducing the stresses that would occur when the rock above the temple's ceilings was removed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] This was accomplished by using chain saws to insert approximately 3.5 feet (1.1 m) deep cuts inside the temples at the junction of the ceilings and walls.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] At the same time work commenced using handsaws to cut grooves as thin as possible into the ceiling, which was supported by felt tipped steel scaffolding.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Rubber sheets were installed to protect the decoration while the cutting was undertaken.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The activities inside the cramped, dust-filled temples required the Italian stonecutters to work in temperatures of 100 °F (38 °C) and higher.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The Joint Venture's contract specified that the weight of the individual blocks was not to exceed 20 tons for the temple chambers and 30 tons for the facades.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] To meet this requirement and to minimize the impact of any cuts, considerable amount of work had gone into selecting where the cuts were to be made.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] However, as they undertook the cutting, the stonecutters would often use their innate feeling for stone to deviate.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Once the cuts had been completed, steel pins were inserted via holes drilled in the cuts to allow the workers on the exterior to determine where to make the cuts that would join with the interior cuts.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] As they would not be seen, these exterior cuts were wider and made with power saws.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Holes were drilled in the separated blocks and steel lifting pins were inserted and epoxied in place with which to lift each block.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] To further protect the blocks from cracking, each was coated with a protective coating.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Any blocks with decorated interior were wrapped in linen.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] After nine months of continuous work by 500 workers, the first block was lifted out on 21 May 1965.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] To lift the blocks, two guy-rope derricks were installed at each temple, one with a 20-ton lifting capacity and the other a 30-ton capacity.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Each block was given a unique identification code (which identified its exact position) and carefully transported on a sand cushion in a slow-moving trailer to one of two temporary holding storage areas with a total area of 44,000 square metres (470,000 sq ft).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] By the time of the first block's removal 3,000 people were living in the construction village, of whom 1,850 were working on site.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] As work progressed on extracting the interiors, the sand was removed from the front of the facades.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] As the heads of figures of the pharaohs on the front of the Great Temple exceeded the 30-ton lifting limit, the weight was reduced by cutting their crown off.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Then on 15 October, the most experienced stone cutters commenced cutting the first face away from behind their ears.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] After this was completed, on the next day the first 19-ton face was removed by the crane.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] To protect them from sandstorms during storage, each block was covered in straw mats, and if necessary given additional applications of resin.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] On 16 April 1966, two weeks ahead of schedule and six months after the disassembly had commenced, the last block was removed, with none having been seriously damaged.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] In total the temples were cut into 1,036 blocks.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Some of the rock and sand used to construct the cofferdam was removed for reuse in creating the new cliff behind the relocated temples, before the rest of the dam was pushed into the rising waters of the lake in late August 1966.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The smallest individual block weighed seven tons.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Meanwhile, in January 1966, work had commenced on constructing the foundations for the relocated temples: 208 m (682 ft) further inland and vertically 65 m (213 ft) higher for the Great Temple, and 67 m (220 ft) for the Small Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The temples were oriented at the new location to duplicate the two occasions each year that the rising sun penetrated the innermost sanctum at the rear of the Great Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] To ensure the correct orientation, the permitted deviation when reassembling the Great Temple was plus or minus 5 mm.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The inner walls and ceilings of the temple were reassembled first.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The interior joints were filled in by specialists from the Department of Antiquities, using a sand paste mixed to match the existing colours; while the wider cuts at the rear were filled in with a cement-based mortar.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The facade of the temples were then reassembled, with the face of the first colossus reunited with its body on 14 September 1966.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] By the end of 1966, the reassembly of the 235 blocks making up the Small Temple was completed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Six weeks later, the reassembly of the 807 blocks making up the Great Temple was completed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] To ensure that there was no weight on the temple interiors and to reduce the amount of backfilling required, a reinforced protective dome was constructed by Hünnebeck GmbH over the rear of each temple after they were completed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The dome for the Great Temple had a span of 55 metres (180 ft) and a height of 19 metres (62 ft), with a loading of 20 tons per square metre at the apex.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] To construct this dome, 2.5 metres (8.2 ft) SL 15 girders were installed to support the formwork for the concrete.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The dome for the Small Temple had a span of 21 metres (69 ft) and a height of 6.6 metres (22 ft).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Over top of these domes, an artificial hill was constructed using 300,000 tons of material removed from the original site to recreate a close approximation of the original setting.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Prior to the project, visitors had to bring their own lamps with them to inspect the interiors of the temples.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] As it was expected that visitor numbers would increase, permanent electric lighting was installed, as well as a mechanical ventilation system hidden in the domes, both for the comfort of visitors and to protect the interior decoration from the effects of temperature and humidity.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] On 22 February 1966, members of the team gathered at sunrise to confirm that the statues of Ramesses, Amun, and Ra-Horakhty were illuminated by the sun's rays, 63.1 metres inside the innermost sanctum of the Great Temple, while that of Ptah was not.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] A further check was made on the other significant date, 22 October.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] By the early summer of 1968 the project was completed, 18 months ahead of schedule.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] On 22 September 1968, 500 people attended the official inauguration of the relocated complex.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Prominent among the guests were the Egyptian Minister of Culture Tharwat Okasha, Egyptologist and leading preservation advocate Christiane Desroches Noblecourt, UNESCO Director-General René Maheu, and Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan, who was a significant fundraiser.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] At the time, the relocation was considered one of the greatest challenges of archaeological engineering in history.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The success of the relocation of Abu Simbel helped the United Nations to introduce a convention establishing the UNESCO World Heritage List.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] The project had cost $41.7 million or 18.5 million Egyptian pounds (equivalent to $436 million in 2025), of which half was borne by Egypt and half provided by international contributions from 48 countries.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] This was approximately 10% higher than the VBB's original estimate.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Today, hundreds of tourists visit the temples daily.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Most visitors arrive by road from Aswan, the nearest city.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] Others arrive by plane at Abu Simbel Airport, an airfield specially constructed in the 1970s to serve the temple complex, with year-round flights to nearby Aswan International Airport and limited seasonal flights to Cairo International Airport.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p01] It was built on the site of the larger of the two temporary holding storage areas used during relocation of the temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The larger one is dedicated to Ra-Horakhty, Ptah and Amun, Egypt's three state deities of the time, and features four large statues of Ramesses II in the facade.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The smaller temple is dedicated to the goddess Hathor, personified by Nefertari, Ramesses's most beloved of his many wives.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The Great Temple at Abu Simbel, which took about twenty years to build, was completed around year 24 of the reign of Ramesses the Great (which corresponds to 1265 BC).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] It was dedicated to the gods Amun, Ra-Horakhty, and Ptah, as well as to the deified Ramesses himself.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] It is generally considered the grandest and most beautiful of the temples commissioned during the reign of Ramesses II, and one of the most beautiful in Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The single entrance is flanked by four colossal, 20 m (66 ft) statues, each representing Ramesses II seated on a throne and wearing the double crown of Upper and Lower Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The statue to the immediate left of the entrance was damaged in an earthquake, causing the head and torso to fall away; these fallen pieces were not restored to the statue during the relocation but placed at the statue's feet in the positions originally found.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The façade behind the colossi is 33 m (108 ft) high and 38 m (125 ft) wide.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] It carries a frieze depicting twenty-two baboons worshipping the rising sun with upraised arms and a stele recording the marriage of Ramesses to a daughter of king Ḫattušili III, which sealed the peace between Egypt and the Hittites.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The entrance doorway itself is surmounted by bas-relief images of the king worshipping the falcon-headed Ra Horakhty, whose statue stands in a large niche.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] Ra holds the hieroglyph *user* and a feather in his right hand, with Maat (the goddess of truth and justice) in his left; this is a cryptogram for Ramesses II's throne name, *User-Maat-Re*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The inner part of the temple has the same triangular layout that most ancient Egyptian temples follow, with rooms decreasing in size from the entrance to the sanctuary.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The temple is complex in structure and quite unusual because of its many side chambers.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The colossal statues along the left-hand wall bear the white crown of Upper Egypt, while those on the opposite side are wearing the double crown of Upper and Lower Egypt (pschent).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The bas-reliefs on the walls of the pronaos depict battle scenes in the military campaigns that Ramesses waged.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] Much of the sculpture is given to the Battle of Kadesh, on the Orontes river in present-day Syria, in which the Egyptian king fought against the Hittites.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The most famous relief shows the king on his chariot shooting arrows against his fleeing enemies, who are being taken prisoner.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] Other scenes show Egyptian victories in Libya and Nubia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] From the hypostyle hall, one enters the second pillared hall, which has four pillars decorated with beautiful scenes of offerings to the gods.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] There are depictions of Ramesses and Nefertari with the sacred boats of Amun and Ra-Horakhty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] This hall gives access to a transverse vestibule, in the middle of which is the entrance to the sanctuary.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] Here, on a black wall, are rock cut sculptures of four seated figures: Ra-Horakhty, the deified king Ramesses, and the gods Amun Ra and Ptah.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] Ra-Horakhty, Amun Ra and Ptah were the main divinities in that period and their cult centers were at Heliopolis, Thebes and Memphis respectively.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] People gather at Abu Simbel on these days to witness this.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] These dates are allegedly the king's birthday and coronation day, respectively.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] There is no direct evidence to support this.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] It is logical to assume, however, that these dates had some relation to a significant event.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] In fact, according to calculations made on the basis of the heliacal rising of the star Sirius (Sothis) and inscriptions found by archaeologists, this date must have been October 22.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] This image of the king was enhanced and revitalized by the energy of the solar star, and the deified Ramesses the Great could take his place next to Amun-Ra and Ra-Horakhty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] Because of the accumulated drift of the Tropic of Cancer due to Earth's axial precession over the past 3 millennia, the event's date must have been different when the temple was built.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] This is compounded by the fact that the temple was relocated from its original setting, so the current alignment may not be as precise as the original one.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The temple of Hathor and Nefertari, also known as the Small Temple, was built about 100 m (330 ft) northeast of the temple of Ramesses II and was dedicated to the goddess Hathor and Ramesses II's chief consort, Nefertari.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] This was in fact the second time in ancient Egyptian history that a temple was dedicated to a queen.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The first time, Akhenaten dedicated a temple to his great royal wife, Nefertiti.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The rock-cut facade is decorated with two groups of colossi that are separated by the large gateway.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The statues, slightly more than 10 m (33 ft) high, are of the king and his queen.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] On either side of the portal are two statues of the king, wearing the white crown of Upper Egypt (south colossus) and the double crown (north colossus); these are flanked by statues of the queen.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] Remarkably, this is one of very few instances in Egyptian art where the statues of the king and his consort have equal size.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] Traditionally, the statues of the queens stood next to those of the pharaoh, but were never taller than his knees.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] Ramesses went to Abu Simbel with his wife in the 24th year of his reign.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] As the Great Temple of the king, there are small statues of princes and princesses next to their parents.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The plan of the Small Temple is a simplified version of that of the Great Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The capitals of the pillars bear the face of the goddess Hathor; this type of column is known as Hathoric.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The bas-reliefs in the pillared hall illustrate the deification of the king, the destruction of his enemies in the north and south (in these scenes the king is accompanied by his wife), and the queen making offerings to the goddesses Hathor and Mut.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The hypostyle hall is followed by a vestibule, access to which is given by three large doors.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] On the south and the north walls of this chamber there are two graceful and poetic bas-reliefs of the king and his consort presenting papyrus plants to Hathor, who is depicted as a cow on a boat sailing in a thicket of papyri.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] On the west wall, Ramesses II and Nefertari are depicted making offerings to the god Horus and the divinities of the Cataracts—Satis, Anubis and Khnum.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The rock-cut sanctuary and the two side chambers are connected to the transverse vestibule and are aligned with the axis of the temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The bas-reliefs on the side walls of the small sanctuary represent scenes of offerings to various gods made either by the pharaoh or the queen.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] On the back wall, which lies to the west along the axis of the temple, there is a niche in which Hathor, as a divine cow, seems to be coming out of the mountain: the goddess is depicted as the Mistress of the temple dedicated to her and to queen Nefertari, who is intimately linked to the goddess.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] Köppen-Geiger climate classification system classifies its climate as hot desert (BWh).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] It is one of the airports in southern Egypt, located 2 km from the city of Abu Simbel.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] At the end of 1964, a committee from the Ministry of Civil Aviation traveled to the Abu Simbel to select a suitable location to serve as an airstrip for Dakota aircraft carrying tourists wishing to visit the Abu Simbel temples.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] This was necessary because the temples were being relocated to their current location due to concerns about them being submerged by Lake Nasser after the construction of the Aswan High Dam.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] This airstrip was built in 1969 with a single 2,000-meter runway and an apron that could accommodate two small aircraft.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] Abu Simbel Airport is currently a domestic airport, but it has the potential to become an international airport in the future.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The temples appear in the 1978 film *Death on the Nile* based on the book of the same name by Agatha Christie.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/abu-simbel-p02] The temples also appear in the 2001 film *The Mummy Returns* as part of the road to Ahm-Shere.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr launched the expedition that conquered Egypt on his own initiative in late 639, defeating the Byzantines in a string of victories ending with the surrender of Alexandria in 641 or 642.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] It was the swiftest of the early Muslim conquests.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] This was followed by westward advances by Amr as far as Tripoli in present-day Libya.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In a treaty signed with the Byzantine governor Cyrus, Amr guaranteed the security of Egypt's population and imposed a poll tax on non-Muslim adult men.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He maintained the Coptic-dominated bureaucracy and cordial ties with the Coptic patriarch Benjamin.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He founded Fustat as the provincial capital with the mosque later called after him at its center.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr ruled relatively independently, acquired significant wealth, and upheld the interests of the Arab conquerors who formed Fustat's garrison in relation to the central authorities in Medina.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After gradually diluting Amr's authority, Caliph Uthman (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 644–656) dismissed him in 646 after accusations of incompetence from his successor Abd Allah ibn Sa'd.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After mutineers from Egypt assassinated Uthman, Amr distanced himself from their cause, despite previously instigating opposition against Uthman.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In the ensuing First Fitna, Amr joined Mu'awiya ibn Abi Sufyan against Caliph Ali (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 656–661) due to promises of the governorship of Egypt and its tax revenues.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr served as Mu'awiya's representative in the abortive arbitration talks to end the war.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Afterward, he wrested control of Egypt from Ali's loyalists, killing its governor Muhammad ibn Abi Bakr, and assumed the governorship instead.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Mu'awiya kept him in his post after establishing the Umayyad Caliphate in 661 and Amr ruled the province until his death.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] His father, al-As ibn Wa'il, was a wealthy landowner from the Banu Sahm clan of the Quraysh tribe of Mecca.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 622, Amr inherited from him the lucrative al-Waht estate and vineyards near Ta'if.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr's mother was al-Nabigha bint Harmala from the Banu Jallan clan of the Anaza tribe.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] She had been taken captive and sold, in succession, to several members of the Quraysh, one of whom was Amr's father.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As such, Amr had two maternal half-brothers, Amr ibn Atatha of the Banu Adi and Uqba ibn Nafi of the Banu Fihr, and a half-sister from the Banu Abd Shams.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr is physically described in the traditional sources as being short with broad shoulders, having a large head with a wide forehead and wide mouth, long arms and a long beard.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] There are conflicting reports about when Amr embraced Islam, with the most credible version placing it in 629/630, not long before the conquest of Mecca by Muhammad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] According to this account, he converted alongside the Qurayshites Khalid ibn al-Walid and Uthman ibn Talha.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] According to Amr's own testimony, transmitted by his fourth-generation descendant Amr ibn Shu'ayb, he converted in Axum in the presence of King Armah (Najashi) and met Muhammad in Medina upon the latter's return from the Battle of Khaybar in 628.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr conditioned his conversion on the forgiveness of his past sins and an "active part in affairs", according to a report cited by the historian Ibn Asakir (d.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Indeed, in October 629, Amr was tasked by Muhammad with leading the raid on Dhat al-Salasil, likely located in the northern Hejaz (western Arabia), a lucrative opportunity for Amr in view of the potential war spoils.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The purpose of the raid is unclear, though the modern historian Fred Donner speculates that it was to "break up a gathering of hostile tribal groups" possibly backed by the Byzantine Empire.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 833) holds that Amr rallied the nomadic Arabs in the region "to make war on [Byzantine] Syria".
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The tribal groups targeted in the raid included the Quda'a in general and the Bali specifically.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr's paternal grandmother hailed from the Bali, and this may have motivated his appointment to the command by Muhammad as Amr was instructed to recruit tribesmen from the Bali and the other Quda'a tribes of Balqayn and Banu Udhra.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Following the raid, a delegation of the Bali embraced Islam.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr further consecrated ties with the tribe by marrying a Bali woman, with whom he had his son Muhammad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Muhammad appointed Amr as the governor of Oman and he remained there until being informed of Muhammad's death in 632.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr was personally chosen by Muhammad to deliver a letter calling the kings of Oman, the Julanda brothers Abd and Jayfa, to convert to Islam while being accompanied by Sa'id ibn Aws al-Ansari.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The death of Muhammad prompted several Arab tribes to defect from the nascent Medina-based Muslim polity in the Ridda wars.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Muhammad's successor Caliph Abu Bakr (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 632–634) appointed Amr to rein in the apostate Quda'a tribes, and among those targeted were the Hejazi branches of the Bali.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr's campaigns, which were supported by the commander Shurahbil ibn Hasana, succeeded in restoring Medina's authority as far as the northern frontier with Syria.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr was one of four commanders dispatched by Abu Bakr to conquer Syria in 633.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The focus of Amr's campaign was Palestine, to which he had been appointed governor by Abu Bakr before his departure.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As a Qurayshite merchant Amr was likely already well-acquainted with the routes to Gaza, a principle terminal for Meccan caravans.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He took the coastal route of the Hejaz, reaching Ayla, a Muslim possession since 630, before breaking west into the Negev desert or possibly the Sinai.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He arrived near the villages of Dathin and Badan in Gaza's environs where he entered into talks with Gaza's Byzantine commander.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After the negotiations broke down, Amr's men bested the Byzantines at the Battle of Dathin on 4 February 634 and set up headquarters at Ghamr al-Arabat in the middle of the Wadi Araba.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Most accounts hold that Amr's army was 3,000-strong; the Muhajirun (emigrants from Mecca to Medina) and the Ansar (natives of Medina), who together formed the core of the earliest Muslim converts, dominated his forces according to al-Waqidi (d.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 823), while the 9th-century historian Ibn A'tham holds that Amr's army consisted of 3,300 Qurayshite and allied horsemen, 1,700 horsemen from the Banu Sulaym and 200 from the Yemenite tribe of Madh'hij.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The historian Philip Mayerson considers the troop figures to be "unquestionably exaggerated" but still representing the largest Arab fighting force to have ever been assembled in southern Palestine and the Sinai until then.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr conquered the area around Gaza by February or March 634 and proceeded to besiege Caesarea, the capital of Byzantine Palestine, in July.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He soon after abandoned the siege upon the approach of a large Byzantine army.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr occupied numerous towns in Palestine, including Bayt Jibrin, Yibna, Amwas, Lydda, Jaffa, Nablus and Sebastia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Most of these localities surrendered after little resistance due to the flight of Byzantine troops; consequently, there is scant information about them in the traditional accounts of the conquest.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 634–644) appointed or confirmed Amr as the commander and governor of the military district of Palestine.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The Muslims pursued the Byzantine army northward and besieged them at Pella for four months.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr may have retained overall command of the Muslim armies until this point, though other accounts assign command to Khalid or Abu Ubayda ibn al-Jarrah.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In any case, the Muslims landed a heavy blow against the Byzantines in the ensuing Battle of Fahl in December 634 or January 635.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Afterward, Amr and Shurahbil may have been sent to besiege Beisan, which capitulated after minor resistance.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The Muslims proceeded to besiege Damascus, where the remnants of the Byzantine army from the battles of Ajnadayn and Fahl had gathered.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr was positioned at the Bab Tuma gate, the Muslim commanders having each been assigned to block one of the city's entrances.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] By August–September 635, Damascus surrendered to the Muslims.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In response to the series of defeats, the Byzantine emperor Heraclius (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Following Yarmouk, the Muslims attempted to capture Jerusalem, where Amr had previously sent an advance force.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Abu Ubayda led the siege of Jerusalem, in which Amr participated, but the city only surrendered after Caliph Umar arrived in person to conclude a treaty with its defenders.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr was one of the witnesses of the Treaty of Umar.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] From Jerusalem, Amr then proceeded to besiege and capture the city of Gaza.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] From his base in southern Palestine, Amr launched the conquest of Byzantine Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He had established trading interests there before his conversion to Islam, making him aware of its importance in international trade.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The traditional Muslim sources generally hold that Amr undertook the campaign with Caliph Umar's reluctant approval, though a number of accounts hold that he entered the region without Umar's authorization.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At the head of 4,000 cavalries and with no siege engines, Amr arrived at the frontier town of al-Arish along the northern Sinai coastline on 12 December 639.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He captured the strategic Mediterranean port city of Pelusium (al-Farama) following a month-long siege and moved against Bilbeis, which also fell after a month-long siege.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr halted his campaign before the fortified Byzantine stronghold of Babylon, at the head of the Nile Delta, and requested reinforcements from Umar.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The latter dispatched al-Zubayr ibn al-Awwam, a leading Qurayshite companion of Muhammad, with a 4,000-strong force, which joined Amr's camp in June 640.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr retained the supreme command of Arab forces in Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In the following month, his army decisively defeated the Byzantines at the Battle of Heliopolis.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He captured Memphis soon after and besieged Babylon.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] During the siege, Amr entered truce negotiations with the Alexandria-based Byzantine governor Cyrus; Emperor Heraclius opposed the talks and recalled Cyrus to Constantinople.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Though strong resistance was put up by Babylon's defenders, their morale was sapped after news of Heraclius' death in February 641.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr made an agreement with the Byzantine garrison, allowing their peaceful withdrawal toward the provincial capital Alexandria on 9 April 641.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr then sent his lieutenants to conquer different parts of the country.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] One of them, Kharija ibn Hudhafa, captured the Fayyum oasis, Oxyrhynchus (Bahnasa), Hermopolis (el-Ashmunein) and Akhmim, all in Middle Egypt, and an unspecified number of villages in Upper Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] It fell virtually without resistance after Cyrus, who had since been restored to office, and Amr finalized a treaty in Babylon guaranteeing the security of Egypt's inhabitants and imposing a poll tax on adult males.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The date of the city's surrender was likely November 642.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Taking advantage of the uncertain political situation in the wake of Umar's death in 644 and the meager Arab military presence in Alexandria, Emperor Constans II (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 641–668) dispatched a naval expedition led by a certain Manuel which occupied the city and killed most of its Arab garrison in 645.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Alexandria's elite and most of the inhabitants assisted the Byzantines; medieval Byzantine, Coptic and, to a lesser extent, Muslim sources indicate the city was not firmly in Arab hands during the preceding three years.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Byzantine forces pushed deeper into the Nile Delta, but Amr forced them back at the Battle of Nikiou.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He besieged and captured Alexandria in the summer of 646; most of the Byzantines, including Manuel, were slain, many of its inhabitants were killed and the city was burned until Amr ordered an end to the onslaught.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Afterward, Muslim rule in Alexandria was gradually solidified.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In contrast to the disarray of the Byzantine defense, the Muslim forces under Amr's command were unified and organized; Amr frequently coordinated with Caliph Umar and his own troops for all major military decisions.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In the absence of siege engines, Amr oversaw long sieges of heavily fortified Byzantine positions, most prominently Babylon, cut supply lines and engaged in long wars of attrition.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He made advantageous use out of the nomads in his ranks, who were seasoned in hit-and-run tactics, and his settled troops, who were generally more acquainted with siege warfare.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] His cavalry-dominated army moved through Egypt's deserts and oases with relative ease.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After the surrender of Alexandria in 642, Amr marched his army westward, bypassing the fortified Byzantine coastal strongholds of Paraetonium (Marsa Matruh), Appolonia Sozusa (Marsa Soussa) and Ptolemais (Tolmeita), capturing Barca and reaching Torca in Cyrenaica.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Toward the end of the year, Amr launched a second cavalry assault targeting Tripoli.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The city was heavily fortified by the Byzantines and contained several naval vessels in its harbor.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Due to his lack of siege engines, he employed the lengthy siege tactic used in the Egyptian conquest.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After about a month, his troops entered Tripoli through a vulnerable point in its walls and sacked the city.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Its fall, which entailed the evacuation by sea of the Byzantine garrison and most of the population, is dated to 642 or 643/44.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Though the Arab hold over Cyrenaica and Zawila to the far south remained firm for decades except for a short-lived Byzantine occupation in 690, Tripoli was recaptured by the Byzantines a few years after Amr's entry.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The region was definitively conquered by the Arabs during the reign of Caliph Abd al-Malik (r.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The mosque was originally founded by Amr in 641 but was redesigned and expanded significantly over the next several centuries.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr "regulated the government of the country [Egypt], administration of justice and the imposition of taxes", according to the historian A.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] During his siege of Babylon, Amr had erected an encampment near the fortress.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He originally intended for Alexandria to serve as the Arabs' capital in Egypt, but Umar rejected this on the basis that no body of water, i.e. the Nile, should separate the caliph from his army.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Instead, following Alexandria's surrender, in 641 or 642, Amr made his encampment near Babylon the permanent garrison town (*miṣr*) of Fustat, the first town founded by the Arabs in Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Its location along the eastern bank of the Nile River and at the head of the Nile Delta and edge of the Eastern Desert strategically positioned it to dominate the Upper and Lower halves of Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Fustat's proximity to Babylon, where Amr also established an Arab garrison, afforded the Arab settlers a convenient means to employ and oversee the Coptic bureaucratic officials who inhabited Babylon and proved critical to running the day-to-day affairs of the Arab government.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr had the original tents of Fustat replaced with mud brick and baked brick dwellings.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Documents found in Hermopolis (al-Ashmunayn) dating from the 640s confirm official orders to forward building materials to Babylon to construct the new city.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The city was organized into allotments over an area stretching 5–6 kilometers (3.1–3.7 mi) along the Nile and 1–2 kilometers (0.62–1.24 mi) inland to the east.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The allotments were distributed among the components of Amr's army, with priority given to the Quraysh, the Ansar and Amr's personal guard, the 'Ahl al-Rāya' (People of the Banner), which included several Bali tribesmen as a result of their kinship and marital ties to Amr.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] An opposing theory holds that Amr did not assign the plots; rather, the tribes staked their own claims and Amr established a commission to resolve the ensuing land disputes.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At the center of the new capital Amr built a congregational mosque, later known as the Amr ibn al-As Mosque; the original structure was frequently redesigned and expanded between its foundation and its final form in 827.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr had his own dwelling built immediately east of the mosque and it most likely served as his government headquarters.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In the northwestern part of Alexandria, Amr built a hilltop congregational mosque, later called after him, before the Byzantine occupation of 645/46, after which he built a second called the Mosque of Mercy; neither mosque has been presently identified.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Adjacent to the congregational mosque, Amr took personal ownership of a fort, which he later donated for government use.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] This part of the city became the administrative and social core of Arab settlement in Alexandria.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Accounts vary as to the number of troops Amr garrisoned in the city, ranging from 1,000 soldiers from the Azd and Banu Fahm tribes to a quarter of the army which was replaced on a rotational basis every six months.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As per the 641 treaty with Cyrus, Amr imposed a poll tax of two gold dinars on non-Muslim adult males.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He imposed other measures, sanctioned by Umar, that entailed the inhabitants' regular provision of wheat, honey, oil and vinegar as a subsistence allowance for the Arab troops.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He had these goods stored in a distribution warehouse called *dār al-rizq*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After taking a census of the Muslims, he further ordered that each Muslim be annually supplied by the inhabitants a highly embroidered wool robe (Egyptian robes were prized by the Arabs), a burnous, a turban, a sirwal (trousers) and shoes.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In a Greek papyrus dated to 8 January 643 and containing Amr's seal (a fighting bull), Amr (transliterated as "Ambros") requests fodder for his army's animals and bread for his soldiers from an Egyptian village.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] According to the historian Martin Hinds, there is "no evidence" that Amr "did anything to streamline the cumbersome fiscal system taken over from the Byzantines; rather, the upheavals of conquest can only have made the system more open to abuse than ever".
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After entering Alexandria, Amr invited the Coptic patriarch Benjamin to return to the city after his years of exile under Cyrus.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The patriarch maintained close ties with Amr and restored the monasteries of Wadi al-Natrun, including the Saint Macarius Monastery, which functions until the present-day.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Kennedy, "Benjamin played a major role in the survival of the Coptic Church through the transition to Arab rule".
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr acted relatively independent as governor and retained much of the surplus tax revenue of the province for the benefit of its troops despite pressure from Umar to forward proceeds to Medina.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He also amassed significant personal wealth in Egypt, part of which was confiscated by Muhammad ibn Maslama on Umar's orders.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At a certain point, the Caliph separated Upper Egypt from Amr's administration and appointed Abd Allah ibn Sa'd over the region.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 644–656) initially kept Amr in his governorship and forged marital links with him by wedding to him his maternal half-sister Umm Kulthum bint Uqba ibn Abi Mu'ayt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Uthman diluted Amr's power in 645/46 by transferring fiscal responsibilities to Ibn Abi Sarh, his own relative, leaving Amr in charge of military affairs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr and Ibn Sa'd lodged complaints to Uthman each alleging the other of incompetence, prompting Uthman to dismiss Amr entirely and replace him in his duties with Ibn Sa'd.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Uthman's appointee established an effective fiscal system that largely preserved its Byzantine predecessor.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Ibn Sa'd reduced the fiscal privileges of Egypt's original Arab military settlers, who had been shown favor by Amr, and secured the remittance of the surplus to Medina.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] This led to the consternation of the Arab garrisons and the native officials and elite, all of whom were "deprived of the opportunities for self-enrichment which they had hitherto enjoyed", according to Hinds.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Open opposition to Ibn Sa'd and Uthman began under the leadership of the Qurayshite Muhammad ibn Abi Hudhayfa in 654/55.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Upon his return to Medina, Amr openly criticized Uthman.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The caliph and Amr engaged in a number of heated public exchanges and, according to a report in the Islamic traditional sources, Amr incited Muhammad's senior companions Ali, al-Zubayr and Talha ibn Ubayd Allah, as well as the Hajj pilgrims in Mecca, against Uthman.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He lobbied Muhammad's wife A'isha for support and the latter pressed Uthman to reappoint Amr to Egypt citing its garrisons' satisfaction with his rule.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In a sermon at the mosque in Medina in June 656 and a letter penned to the Muslim leaders in Syria, Uthman mentioned that he had intended to reappoint Amr but did not follow through as a result of the latter's excessive insult.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After his last exchange with Uthman, Amr retired to his estate in southern Palestine.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 1226) also suggest that Ajlan was located in the area of Bayt Jibrin.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr had likely become owner of the estate through a caliphal grant, though he possibly could have taken possession of it in the course of his conquest of Palestine and his ownership had been confirmed by the caliphs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He lived on the estate, where he derived agricultural revenue, with his sons Muhammad and Abd Allah.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At his estate Amr received news of the siege of Uthman's house and the caliph's subsequent assassination by Amr's Egyptian partisans.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The roughly 400–600 Egyptian mutineers had protested Uthman's fiscal centralization policies in Medina and accused him of favoring his relatives over the early Muslim converts.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The caliph had initially persuaded them to withdraw, but when they intercepted a letter on their departure ordering Ibn Abi Sarh to punish them, they turned back and assaulted Uthman in his home.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In an anecdote cited by al-Baladhuri, Amr is quoted as taking partial credit for Uthman's assassination.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Ali succeeded Uthman, but did not reappoint Amr to his post in Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr was one of a number of figures held culpable for Uthman's death by the slain caliph's clan, the Banu Umayya (Umayyads), most prominently by Uthman's uterine brother and Amr's former brother-in-law al-Walid ibn Uqba.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Nonetheless the governor of Syria, which included Palestine, the Umayyad Mu'awiya ibn Abi Sufyan, had left Amr on his estate undisturbed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As pressure from the Umayyads increased against him, Amr distanced himself from any role in Uthman's death and wrote Mu'awiya to execute or banish the participating Egyptian troops who had been apprehended as they passed through Mu'awiya's jurisdiction on their way back to Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After Ali's victory against al-Zubayr, Talha and Aisha at the Battle of the Camel in Iraq, Mu'awiya, who maintained his opposition to Ali, became the focus of the Caliph's attention.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Mu'awiya summoned Amr to discuss an alliance against Ali.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In the ensuing negotiations, Amr pressed Mu'awiya for lifetime possession of Egypt, to which Mu'awiya ultimately acceded after being persuaded by his brother Utba ibn Abi Sufyan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The public agreement, composed by Amr's *mawlā* Wardan and made in Jerusalem, secured Amr's allegiance to Mu'awiya in return for the latter's assistance in gaining control of Egypt from Ali's governor.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] To secure the defense of his Syrian realm from Ali's loyalists in Egypt, Amr counseled Mu'awiya to secure the support of the Judhamite chief in Palestine, Natil ibn Qays, by ignoring his seizure of the district treasury; Natil subsequently joined Mu'awiya's cause.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr then advised Mu'awiya to lead the Syrian army in person against Ali, who began his march toward Syria in late May 657.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] When Ali's Iraqi forces set up camp around Siffin, south of the Euphrates town of Raqqa, in early June, Mu'awiya's advance guard led by Abu al-A'war refused them access to the watering places under their control.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After Ali protested, Amr advised Mu'awiya to accept their request as preventing access to water might rally the hitherto demotivated Iraqis to a determined fight against the Syrians.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Mu'awiya refused and the Iraqis subsequently defeated the Syrians led by Amr and Abu al-A'war in a skirmish known as the "Day of the Euphrates".
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As the leader of the Syrian cavalry, Amr held the overall field command for Mu'awiya's forces in the ensuing weeks-long Battle of Siffin and on occasion personally participated in direct combat, though without particular distinction.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At one point in the battle, he raised a black fabric given to him by Muhammad at the tip of his spear, symbolizing the command role given to him by Muhammad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As the Iraqis gained the battlefield advantage, Amr proposed to Mu'awiya that their men tie leaves from the Qur'an at the tips of their lances in an appeal to Ali's men to settle the conflict peacefully.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] It served as a successful ruse which ended the fighting as the battle turned in Ali's favor and sowed uncertainty in Ali's ranks.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The Caliph heeded the majority will in his army to settle the matter diplomatically; an arbitration was agreed with Amr representing Mu'awiya and Abu Musa al-Ash'ari representing Ali.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr met with Ali once and the two exchanged insults, but Ali ultimately agreed to Amr's condition that he omit his caliphal title, *amir al-mu'minin* (commander of the faithful), from the preliminary arbitration document drafted on 2 August.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The omission effectively placed Ali and Mu'awiya on an equal political footing and thereby weakened Ali's leadership position over the Muslim polity.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr and Abu Musa likely met twice, at Dumat al-Jandal and then Adhruh, to forge an agreement.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At Dumat al-Jandal, Amr succeeded in gaining Abu Musa's recognition that Uthman was wrongfully killed, a verdict opposed by Ali and which strengthened Syrian support for Mu'awiya, who had taken up the cause of revenge for the death of his kinsman Uthman.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At the last meeting in Adhruh, the office of the caliphate was discussed, but the meeting ended in violence and without agreement; during the brawl, Amr was physically assaulted by a Kufan partisan of Ali, but the latter was fended off by one of Amr's sons.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Abu Musa retired to Mecca, while Amr and the Syrians returned to Mu'awiya and recognized him as **amir al-mu'minin** before formally pledging allegiance to him in April/May 658.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As a result, Amr was among those invoked in a ritual curse issued by Ali during the morning prayers and became the subject of derision among the Kufan core of Ali's supporters.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As early as 656/57, Amr and Mu'awiya persuaded Ibn Abi Hudhayfa, who had seized control of Egypt after Uthman's assassination, to meet them in al-Arish, where they took him captive in a ruse.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr and Mu'awiya did not advance further than this point and Ibn Abi Hudhayfa was executed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Ali's second governor in Egypt, Qays ibn Sa'd, was dismissed in late 657 due to concerns that he would defect to Mu'awiya and his next appointee, Malik ibn al-Harith, died in Qulzum (Suez) on his way to the province.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Malik's replacement was Muhammad ibn Abi Bakr, son of the first caliph and a foster son of Ali.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Ibn Abi Bakr burned the homes and arrested the families of pro-Uthman mutineers from the Fustat garrison led by Mu'awiya ibn Hudayj and Maslama ibn Mukhallad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The latter two requested intervention by Mu'awiya, who dispatched Amr to Egypt with a 4,000–6,000-strong army.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Despite his thirteen-year absence from Egypt, Amr nonetheless mustered the support of Egypt's original Arab military settlers and their sons.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In July/August 658, his forces defeated Ali's troops at the Battle of al-Musannah between Heliopolis (Ain Shams) and Fustat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Ibn Hudayj pursued and captured Ibn Abi Bakr and had him executed over the objections of Amr, who had been lobbied by Ibn Abi Bakr's brother Abd al-Rahman to spare his life.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As per his agreement with Mu'awiya, Amr was installed as governor of Egypt for life and ruled as a virtual partner rather than a subordinate of Mu'awiya, who had become caliph after Ali's assassination and his son Hasan's abdication in 661.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] On 22 January of that year, Amr escaped an assassination attempt by the Kharijite Zadawayh or Amr ibn Bakr, who killed Amr's stand-in for the Friday prayers, Kharija ibn Hudhafa, mistaking the latter for Amr.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] When the Kharijite was apprehended and brought before him, Amr proclaimed "You wanted me, but God wanted Kharija!" and he personally executed him.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr was permitted by the Caliph to retain personally the surplus revenues of the province after the payment of the troops' stipends and other government expenses.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He increased the original garrison at Fustat, numbering some 15,000 soldiers, with the Syrian troops he brought with him.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] According to the historian Clive Foss "Amr ruled the country successfully, and with considerable independence and privilege, until his death".
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr died of natural causes over the age of 79.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Accounts vary regarding the date of his death, though the most credible versions place it in 43 AH (663–664 CE).
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He was buried at the foot of the Muqattam hills to the east of Fustat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Due to the early Muslims' reticence to mark the graves of their dead, Amr's burial place has not been identified.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In a testament to the personal wealth that he accrued, at the time of his death he left seventy sacks of gold dinars.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] His sons Abd Allah and Muhammad refused inheritance of the sums, which were then confiscated by Mu'awiya.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Abd Allah succeeded his father as governor for a few weeks until Mu'awiya replaced him with his own brother Utba.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The traditional Egypt-based Arabic and Coptic sources regard Amr positively.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The major source of information about the Muslim conquest of Egypt and the province's early Arab military generations, Ibn Abd al-Hakam (d.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 871), commends Amr for his leadership of the Egyptian conquest and as the upholder of the interests of Egypt's troops and their families against the central authorities in Medina and later Damascus.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The Egyptian Arab tradition holds that Amr was personally praised by Muhammad and was a man of wisdom and piety on his deathbed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The nearly contemporary Coptic historian John of Nikiu (fl.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Though demographically Egypt remained largely non-Arab and non-Muslim for centuries after the conquest, the country has been continuously ruled by Muslims until the present day.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr's estates in Palestine remained in the possession of his descendants as late as the 10th or 11th centuries.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] His granddaughter Umm Abd Allah bint Abd Allah married the Umayyad viceroy of Egypt Abd al-Aziz ibn Marwan (d.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 705) and gave birth to his sons Suhayl and Sahl and daughters Sahla and Umm al-Hakam.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The estates in Medina that Amr's descendants inherited from him were confiscated by the Abbasids after they took over the Caliphate from the Umayyads in 750.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The estates were restored to Amr's family after the intercession of his great-granddaughter Abida al-Hasna bint Shu'ayb ibn Abd Allah, who married the Abbasid prince al-Husayn ibn Abd Allah ibn Ubayd Allah ibn Abbas (d.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Epipaleolithic Natufians carried parthenocarpic figs from Africa to the southeastern corner of the Fertile Crescent, c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Later migrations out of the Fertile Crescent would carry early agricultural practices to neighboring regions—westward to Europe and North Africa, northward to Crimea, and eastward to Mongolia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] The ancient people of the Sahara imported domesticated animals from Asia between 6000 and 4000 BCE.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] In Nabta Playa by the end of the 7th millennium BCE, prehistoric Egyptians had imported goats and sheep from Southwest Asia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Foreign artifacts dating to the 5th millennium BCE in the Badarian culture in Egypt indicate contact with distant Syria.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] In predynastic Egypt, by the beginning of the 4th millennium BCE, ancient Egyptians in Maadi were importing pottery as well as construction ideas from Canaan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] By the 4th millennium BCE shipping was well established, and the donkey and possibly the dromedary had been domesticated.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Domestication of the Bactrian camel and use of the horse for transport then followed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Charcoal samples found in the tombs of Nekhen, which were dated to the Naqada I and II periods, have been identified as cedar from Lebanon.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Predynastic Egyptians of the Naqada I period also imported obsidian from Ethiopia, used to shape blades and other objects from flakes.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] The Naqadans traded with Nubia to the south, the oases of the western desert to the west, and the cultures of the eastern Mediterranean to the east.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Pottery and other artifacts from the Levant that date to the Naqadan era have been found in ancient Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Egyptian artifacts dating to this era have been found in Canaan and other regions of the Near East, including Tell Brak, Uruk and Susa in Mesopotamia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Tell es-Sakan was an Egyptian settlement in the southern Levant (present-day Palestine) and acted as a trading post for goods travelling between the region and Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] By the second half of the 4th millennium BCE, the gemstone lapis lazuli was being traded from its only known source in the ancient world—Badakhshan, in what is now northeastern Afghanistan—as far as Mesopotamia and Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] The overland route through the Wadi Hammamat from the Nile to the Red Sea was known as early as predynastic times; drawings depicting Egyptian reed boats have been found along the path dating to 4000 BCE.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Ancient cities dating to the First Dynasty of Egypt arose along both its Nile and Red Sea junctions, testifying to the route's ancient popularity.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] It became a major route from Thebes to the Red Sea port of Elim, where travelers then moved on to either Asia, Arabia or the Horn of Africa.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Records exist documenting knowledge of the route among Senusret I, Seti, Ramesses IV and also, later, the Roman Empire, especially for mining.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] The Darb el-Arbain trade route, passing through Kharga in the south and Asyut in the north, was used from as early as the Old Kingdom of Egypt for the transport and trade of gold, ivory, spices, wheat, animals and plants.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Later, Ancient Romans would protect the route by lining it with varied forts and small outposts, some guarding large settlements complete with cultivation.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Described by Herodotus as a road "traversed ... in forty days", it became by his time an important land route facilitating trade between Nubia and Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Its maximum extent was northward from Kobbei, 25 miles north of al-Fashir, passing through the desert, through Bir Natrum and Wadi Howar, and ending in Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Shipbuilding was known to the Ancient Egyptians as early as 3000 BCE, and perhaps earlier.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] Ancient Egyptians knew how to assemble planks of wood into a ship hull, with woven straps used to lash the planks together, and reeds or grass stuffed between the planks helped to seal the seams.
[src:ancient-egyptian-trade/ancient-egyptian-trade] The Archaeological Institute of America reports that the earliest dated ship—75 feet long, dating to 3000 BCE—may have possibly belonged to Pharaoh Aha.
